\par\par \b \uc2  Premature euphoria. \b0\par\par\uc2 668 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 July 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers have of late been congratulating themselves on the remarkable signs of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  improvement over the last two months, especially after the peaceful parliamentary elections in early June. Given the presidential election in November, the timing of the bullish indicators couldn't be better for supporters of President B.J. Habibie, who are already campaigning for his second tenure. They were, predictably, quick to capitalize on the situation, touting the impressive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators as a market vote of confidence for the Habibie administration. \par \par \uc2  Chief \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita declared that recovery is already underway. He foresaw \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth much higher than the 0.13 percent predicted by the Central Bureau of Statistics for the whole year, compared to a contraction of almost 14 percent in 1998. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Sjahril Sabirin was equally bullish, predicting a single-digit inflation rate, as against 78 percent last year, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  below 17 percent, down from 35 percent in January, and a rupiah range of Rp 6,000 to Rp 6,500 to the U.S. dollar. The composite index of the Jakarta Stock Exchange, which fell to as low as 393.62 in March, is now hovering above 655. The financial market seems to believe that the worst is over and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis has bottomed out. \par \par \uc2  However welcome and essential are the signs of recovery for confidence building, especially for the beleaguered business sector, the high sense of euphoria is still premature. The more damaging it would be to the incipient recovery if the bullish sentiments prompted an easing of the implementation of painful reform measures. As core problems remain and the fate of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is being held hostage to the outcome of the presidential election in November and the credibility of the new government to be formed in December, it is doubtful whether the budding recovery will hold. \par \par \uc2  Problem is indicators from \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals are not heartening. Exports for the first five months were down more than 10 percent from the same period last year, despite the 65 percent depreciation of the rupiah. Imports in the same period decreased 13.3 percent, indicating persisting low capacity utilization at most manufacturing plants. \par \par \uc2  Direct investment is a far more important indicator of recovery than the upbeat trend in the highly speculative financial market. Unfortunately, new direct foreign capital inflows are still negligible. Except for new small investments and foreign acquisition of some assets, such as Standard Chartered Bank's investment in Bank Bali, foreign investors do not appear eager for local assets offered by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency. This is quite disappointing because assets in the country should be the cheapest in Southeast Asia now, given the almost 65-percent depreciation of the rupiah against the dollar and the 78-percent inflation last year. Asset purchases by foreign investors in Thailand and South Korea have been very much part of the fuel that generates \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in the two countries. \par \par \uc2  The major hurdles to new direct investment in Indonesia are quite obvious. The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about law enforcement and the upcoming transition to a new government has made the risk of investing in the country unusually high. \par \par \uc2  Other major barriers to the recovery process are the agonizingly slow pace of the bank restructuring and resolution of the US$70 billion in corporate foreign debts and Rp 235 trillion ($34.5 billion) in bad debts of domestic banks. \par \par \uc2  As long as these problems are not resolved satisfactorily, exports will remain hindered by a lack of trade financing as most foreign banks will continue to shun Indonesian companies. Domestic banks will also have difficulty finding viable businesses to finance if the huge bad debt overhang is not resolved. Since the almost 1,700 bad debtors, currently being treated at the IBRA 'hospital', are themselves the main players in upstream and downstream manufacturing industries, the real sector will remain virtually moribund, deprived of working capital, and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals will remain on shaky ground. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv7a00aor\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
