\par\par \b \uc2  How fares Soeharto? \b0\par\par\uc2 654 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 July 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  As the Dutch say, hoge bomen vangen veel wind (tall trees catch much wind). During the 32 years that Soeharto was president of Indonesia, even the slightest sign of illness was enough to set off rumors of a power struggle within the political elite and rattle the market. \par \par \uc2  Those years are over, of course. But even after his fall from power in May last year, it cannot be denied that Indonesia's former second president continues to exert a considerable influence, at least in certain segments of our community. How else to explain the persistent speculation circulating at present that the former strongman is still pulling strings behind the scene to ensure the new government that will emerge after the November presidential elections will be favorably inclined toward protecting him and his clan's interests? \par \par \uc2  For that reason there is no cause to feel either shocked, surprised or resentful - depending on the kind of emotional relationship one has with the ex-president - about the seemingly nosy attitude the media has been displaying around the Pertamina Hospital sickroom and facilities where Soeharto is being treated after a mild stroke he is said to have suffered last Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  Soeharto is the former chief executive of Southeast Asia's biggest country and the fourth most populous in the world. He is the man who, during his long tenure, managed, among other things, to raise the standard of life for millions of Indonesians, even if much of that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress later turned out to be hollow in many important sectors due to rampant power abuse and mismanagement. \par \par \uc2  Soeharto, at the same time, is the man who, through his iron-fisted rule, fashioned the executive branch of government into a power apparatus so overbearing, it turned the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  and judiciary branches, together with the military, into mere subordinate extensions of the state's executive powers. Soeharto is the man who effectively dealt a death blow to democracy after his predecessor, Sukarno, stunted its functioning by his introduction of "guided democracy". Soeharto, in other words, was the main architect of much of what was both good and bad in this country's most recent past. \par \par \uc2  At this moment, even in his present impaired condition - or perhaps because of it - Soeharto continues to draw the attention of millions of Indonesians. For one thing, the legal process of going after his and his family's alleged personal wealth with which his successor, B.J. Habibie, is burdened by \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  order, has barely started and is now dangling in \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . For another, many Indonesians are watching with interest what Soeharto's illness and possible permanent disability could have on the process of electing a new president for the country in November. \par \par \uc2  Given the huge impact Soeharto's legacy still has on the lives of so many Indonesians, it would be needless to say the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  has a right to be accurately informed of the former president's condition. Under these circumstances, Indonesians think with envy of how most modern democratic countries release reliable information to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  in times such as these. \par \par \uc2  Surely, especially considering the precarious times in which Indonesians are living at present, it is better - if worse comes to worse - to have our medical authorities handle the task of informing the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the same way American doctors did during President Reagan's illness or President Eisenhower's demise, rather than to shroud Soeharto in the same kind of secrecy Russian doctors did with Stalin at the time of the Soviet leader's death. \par \par \uc2  One more suggestion to conclude this commentary: It would help if somebody in the family could tell Soeharto's legal advisors to stop issuing medical statements and leave this particular task to the medical authorities in charge. Too much confusion has already been caused by one and all giving out contrary statements about the ex-president's condition. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv7o003yk\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'Greenspan statement wreaks havoc on world bourses'. \b0\par\par\uc2 472 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 July 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The composite indexes of major international bourses fell in the wake of a statement made on Thursday by the Fed's Allan Greenspan, who said that he might raise \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a move to stem inflation in the US, said market analyst Dandossi Matram. \par \par \uc2  The JSX composite index (IHSG) yesterday dropped 16.825 points.In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng index fell 275.35 points (2.05%) to 13093.70, followed by the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) Comp with 21.43 points (2.58%) to 808.34 and the index of the Nikkei-225 in Tokyo by 195.9 points (1.10%) to 17534.44.The same fate befell the Straits Times of Singapore with 77.74 points (3.76%) to 1990.15 and the Seoul Comp 71.7 points (7.34%) to 904.96. \par \par \uc2  He said Greenspan's statement on \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused investment managers to get out of equity and bonds.Official data indicate that the US is heading towards higher inflation as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is growing too fast.Unless high levels of production are met by demand, he said, overheating will take place. \par \par \uc2  Greenspan also sees higher GDP in 1999 by 2.5%-3% to 3.5%-3.75%."The US' growth rate is at its pinnacle. This indicates that the Fed is set to raise \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he told Bisnis here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Dandossi also noted that regional bourses fell as foreign investment managers let go their investments in Asean equity and bonds in anticipation of a weaker dollar.This, he added, caused bourses to be stagnant as a rise in US \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would have a negative impact on the rupiah and cause \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Michael Ng, the deputy managing director of Sassoon Securities, said there are other reasons besides Greenspan's statement that lie behind the weakening of Asian bourses, one of which is inter-bank rates in Hong Kong that rose on Friday. In addition, the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Mainland China over its currency, the yuan, tension between China and Taiwan and the ban by Beijing over the religious sect Falun Gong. \par \par \uc2  He predicted that the Hang Seng index is set to continue falling to 12,000, according to Reuters. This is in contrast to Singapore, whose bourse fell because of Greenspan's statement. In Tokyo, share prices dropped because of Greenspan's statement and fears over a stronger yen. \par \par \uc2  The dollar was traded at 117.25 yen in Tokyo, at 116.57 yen in New York. In Seoul, the fall was due to higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investor panic over the financial plight of the Daewoo Group. At the HSX, trading stood at 862,984,560 shares worth Rp592,586,316,000 with a frequency of 18,779. (rn/shm). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv7o001a1\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pich