\par\par \b \uc2  Cell phones ring up profits in crisis. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Yudha Kartohadiprodjo \par \uc2 1,308 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 August 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Many residents of major cities cling to their cellular phones as a necessity. The Jakarta Post looks at the business and the thriving black market for the sought-after products. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Walking through the corridors of Roxy Mas Mall, West Jakarta, one could be forgiven for mistaking the outlet of a cellular phone vendor for a candy store. Attractively placed behind glass cases, cellular phone sets in various colors, models and brands are displayed to catch the eye of passersby. \par \par \uc2  Feeling blue or green today? Nusaphone, a small vendor in a corner of the mall, carries Nokia 5110 phones in eight gradations of blue. Into the high-tech look? The Samsung phone set that Nusaphone sells comes in two metallic colors. \par \par \uc2  Sometimes, however, the pretty packaging is deceiving. \par \par \uc2  Windi, a photographer, bought his cellular phone a month ago in Roxy Mas. The phone worked fine for the first five days. His job requires him to be reachable at any hour and he rarely turned the phone off. \par \par \uc2  One day, however, the message "SIM card not recognized" suddenly flashed on the phone's display screen. \par \par \uc2  "I took the phone back to the store. They acknowledged the problem and explained that the phone was made for the German market, but they refused to take back the phone." \par \par \uc2  Unwittingly, Windi bought a black market phone set, known as BM or Nonguaranteed (Non-G) goods among cellular phone vendors. \par \par \uc2  High demand from consumers and the exceptionally competitive market are driving the black market. Of course, no \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  are paid when the goods are smuggled into the country and the purchaser does not receive a warranty. \par \par \uc2  The price difference between a phone bought from a certified vendor and one from the black market is about Rp 200,000. \par \par \uc2  A cell phone distributor, "Boy", said the items were smuggled into the country through forwarder companies who "take care" of the delivery and customs. \par \par \uc2  Most of them arrive at major gateways of Batam, Jakarta and Surabaya as hand-carried cargo goods. \par \par \uc2  "Want to order 100 sets of phones? Just call a distributor in Singapore or Hong Kong. If the price is right, they would then contact a forwarder who would offer their services for a mere Rp 60,000 per piece. \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  free and right to your door," Boy said. \par \par \uc2  Services are abruptly halted when the customs agency declares "red light" operations, a code that means it is tightening its inspections. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  free? Seems like an offer no profit-minded businessperson could refuse. \par \par \uc2  Yet the government is losing a lot of money but doing nothing, despite the ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to stop the inflow of smuggled phones. \par \par \uc2  Currently, 50,000 phone sets are sold in Indonesia every month and luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and customs duties are not paid on about 50 percent of the sales. With the average price of a cellular phone costing about Rp 1.5 million (about US$200) each, the state's monthly loss is estimated at Rp 8 billion. The number accounts for nearly one third of the state's total \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  losses for all electronic goods combined. \par \par \uc2  Customs officials appear to have turned a blind eye to the problem. \par \par \uc2  "Well, yeah, sometimes there is hand-carried (cargo) but the amount usually is not enough for trading. If we caught a shipment, we would impose the usual custom duty," said Tony Soesanto, head of the customs service office at Soekarno-Hatta International Airport. \par \par \uc2  Tony also denied knowing of the terms "red light" or "green light". \par \par \uc2  Still, he cannot deny the fact that many cellular phone vendors are more than happy to sell warranty-less phones. \par \par \uc2  "The market is so competitive nowadays and our customers always want to have the lowest price," said Boy. He added that the net profit for vendors is low; for each phone set sold, the margin for vendors usually does not exceed Rp 75,000. \par \par \uc2  What the vendors lose in profit they make up for in volume. On average, a small vendor in Roxy Mas easily sells 100 phone sets per month. \par \par \uc2  The demand for cellular phone sets, assisted by the introduction of the prepaid GSM card, is exceeding what suppliers can handle. Prior to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, there were 1.2 million cellular service subscribers. The number tailed off to 800,00 when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stumbled. \par \par \uc2  Industry experts predicted the number would not recover until the end of this year. But reports reveal that the number of subscribers exceeded 1.6 million by the middle of the year. \par \par \uc2  Cellular phones have only recently come into their own as a mass consumer product. \par \par \uc2  Many remember that the only thing close to a cell phone in the 1980s was a dull, heavy black box connected to a long antenna. \par \par \uc2  The phone, either produced by PT INTI, Dancall or Ericsson, was only practical for use as a car phone. \par \par \uc2  Costing from Rp 14 million to Rp 18 million apiece when the rupiah still traded at about 1,200 to the U.S., its price kept it out of the hands of all but the wealthiest of consumers. \par \par \uc2  It is only in the past three years, riding the wave of the decade's boom times, that ownership of a cellular phone developed into a trend. \par \par \uc2  The strengthening of the rupiah in recent months before last week's plunge also increased the sales of cellular phones in Jakarta. The Ericsson GF788, which cost Rp 2.2 million last year, now is offered at Rp 1.35 million. Some models even sell for less than Rp 1 million. \par \par \uc2  "We usually keep our price close to the phone's real value in dollars. As the average price decreases by Rp 600,000, demand starts to hike up," said Adi Saputra, director of PT Sarindon Nusapersada, a distributor of Samsung cellular phones. \par \par \uc2  Adi said consumers increasingly sought sophisticated phones as status symbols. "It's the prestige over price and functionality." \par \par \uc2  Dual-band \par \par \uc2  Dual-band phones, which can receive signals on both the GSM 900 and GSM 1800 frequencies, are the sought-after choice at the moment. \par \par \uc2  Indonesian operators can only support the GSM 900 frequency currently and the prohibitive cost of the dual band makes the prospect of an upgrade unlikely at any time soon. \par \par \uc2  "Although nobody could fully use the feature unless they go abroad, it seems that dual-band is the trend for now," said Adi. \par \par \uc2  The same trend is also noticed by Susanto Susilo, a director of PT Ericsson Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Susanto said the company did not lose money to the black market. "It just adds an extra job for us, since we receive more complaints. But as long as consumers still buy Ericsson, it's fine with us." \par \par \uc2  To educate its consumers, Ericsson places advertisements in the media and has set up a consumer hot line. \par \par \uc2  Consumer ignorance about the advantages of purchasing a model inclusive of a warranty appears to fan the growth of the black market. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Consumers Foundation (YLKI) says that consumers' lack of trust in the warranty system reflects their preference for choosing black market goods. \par \par \uc2  "In their mind, consumers are asking for thorough coverage from the warranty. In reality, most warranties only cover the service charge, which is actually not expensive," said YLKI's Tini Hadad. \par \par \uc2  Most of the complaints to the agency concerning electronic goods involved poor after-sales service. \par \par \uc2  YLKI said companies should provide complete warranty terms and also assure that they cover not only services but spare parts. \par \par \uc2  Consumers also are advised to shun the black market because it they could end up with a dud. \par \par \uc2  "Buying a black market phone means that the service terms for the set are \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and there is a chance that no compatible spare parts are available in Indonesia," Tini added. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv8f003tm\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'Bappenas too optimistic on 4% growth'. \b0\par\par\uc2 383 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 August 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Bappenas' forecast which said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can grow from 2%-4% in this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year is considered as being too optimistic given the majority of companies have not begun producing. \par \par \uc2  "Next year's growth will only reach 2.6%. This year is still around 1%-2%. It is too high to say 4%," \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  observer Anggito Abimanyu told Bisnis in Jakarta yesterday. \par \par \uc2  According to Anggito, the current national production capacity is still very low. The machines that are suppose to produce the raw materials that are needed for exports are still not operating, he said. \par \par \uc2  If the government sets such a high target, it would bring a bad impact on the macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability. \par \par \uc2  One of the key to growth lies on exports, said Anggito. If exports are boosted, while the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was not yet moving, the capital used to spin the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  wheel has to be imported. \par \par \uc2  "The imports will ruin the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth because it will bring a problem to the balance of trade. Import means negative GDP [gross domestic product]," said Anggito. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  observer Pande Radja Silalahi said the government was still having problem in moving the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  because of lack of fund in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  If the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  gets better in the near term, the government will be able to receive more income from the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  so it can finance expenditures, said Silalahi. \par \par \uc2  "Right now we cannot tell whether or not the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is getting worst because of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the political situation," he said. \par \par \uc2  According to Anggito, if the government sets a high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, it will at the same time sacrifice the macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability as import volume will rise and it will in turn damage the balance of trade. \par \par \uc2  Anggito further added that Indonesia has to import raw materials if it wishes to boost exports because local companies cannot yet meet its full capacity. \par \par \uc2  "My prediction is that exports can grow 10%, but imports will reach 16% due to the rupiah appreciation and the inability of the local production capacity to recover," said Anggito. \par \par \uc2  According to him, Indonesia had a chance to increase its export volume. But with the recent rupiah appreciation, exports is becoming difficult again and product competitiveness is low. (msw). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv8k001e6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
