\par\par \b \uc2  GDP growth in 1999/2000 predicted at 2-4%. \b0\par\par\uc2 761 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 August 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): State Minister and Chairman of the National Development Planning Board (Bappenas) Boediono forecast on Tuesday that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow by between 2 percent and 4 percent in the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year ending in March 2000. \par \par \uc2  He also projected that growth would expand to a range of 4 percent to 6 percent in the next \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  "With growth prospects of 2 to 4 percent this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year and 4 to 6 percent next year, the next two years could witness the recovery of over half of our income per capita, measured in U.S dollars, lost during the crisis," Boediono told a capital market seminar. \par \par \uc2  He believed that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would see a gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate of between 6 percent and 7 percent in the 2003/2004 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  "In per capita dollar terms, Indonesian GDP will be back to pre-crisis levels but on a more sustainable growth path with lower inflation, a stable exchange rate, lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and a sustainable government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Boediono said. \par \par \uc2  Boediono's growth forecast for the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year is rosier than the 1.5 percent to 2.5 percent predicted earlier in July. The forecast appears optimistic in view of a major bank scandal and increasing political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But Boediono said: "In terms of our resource base, human and physical capital, our capacity to rebound is great. What we need is a good political climate, good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and, yes, a little luck." \par \par \uc2  Indonesia has been badly hit by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis that started in the middle of 1997. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  contracted by 13.68 percent last year, inflation skyrocketed to more than 77 percent, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark interest rate soared to more than 70 percent and the rupiah plunged to as low as Rp 17,000 to the U.S. dollar, compared to Rp 2,500 before the crisis. \par \par \uc2  But the rupiah has managed to stabilize at between 7,000 to 8,000 over the past few months, inflation has continued to be negative for five months in a row, the benchmark interest plunged to around 13 percent and there was positive GDP growth in the second quarter. \par \par \uc2  Boediono emphasized the importance of continuing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform programs to achieve sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  "We believe that the key to getting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  growing lies in bank restructuring, corporate restructuring, reducing the impediments to doing business, and in legal judicial reform," he said. \par \par \uc2  Boediono expected the rupiah to trade at 6,000 to 8,000 against the dollar next year, depending on the strength of private capital inflows, but gave no timeframe. \par \par \uc2  Inflation is expected to stabilize at 3 percent to 4 percent and the nominal deposit interest rate to fall to the 6 percent to 10 percent range, he said. \par \par \uc2  The government plans to raise revenue by several percentage points of the GDP and cut \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but will still face \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits over the next few years, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Five years from now, we believe that we can successfully eliminate the need for net foreign inflows and any need to have recourse to financing," Boediono said. \par \par \uc2  "Our \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will reach an overall balance," he added. \par \par \uc2  "This \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  scenario is in line with our objective to achieve \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability in the medium term," Boediono said, adding that Indonesia should experience current account surpluses for the next few years before returning to a small \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the World Bank vice president for East Asia and the Pacific Jean-Michel Severino said in a speech at the same meeting that it was important to continue the bank restructuring program. \par \par \uc2  "But let there be no mistake, the recapitalization of banks is not the end of the process - it is just the beginning," he said. \par \par \uc2  Severino added that while it was necessary for the government to nationalize several major banks to prevent the collapse of the banking system, "This is neither desirable nor healthy for the long-run development of a sound and efficient banking system. \par \par \uc2  "Restructuring the state banks and then privatizing them must be a central focus of attention in the future," he added. \par \par \uc2  Severino also warned that it was crucial for the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) to restore its image following the Bank Bali scandal. \par \par \uc2  "IBRA also has an important fiduciary role which must be taken seriously," he said, adding that given the agency's importance, it would itself inevitably be accused of negligence or wrongdoing. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv8p004b3