\par\par \b \uc2  Life insurance industry manages well amid crisis. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Tertiani ZB Simanjuntak. \par \uc2 809 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 September 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Unlike the country's ailing banking sector, the life insurance industry has fared well in coping with the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  According to the Indonesian Insurance Council, growth of premium income of the life insurance industry surged by 32.77 percent to Rp 4.86 trillion (about US$648 million) last year despite the crisis. \par \par \uc2  The 1998 growth level was below the 38 percent level recorded in 1996, but it was far higher than the 27 percent in 1997. \par \par \uc2  The council estimates that the life insurance industry will fare better this year given the significant increase in the premium income recorded by major life insurance players in the first semester of this year. \par \par \uc2  Several major life insurance companies, mostly foreign joint ventures, have aggressively launched their latest products to win a larger slice of the growing market. \par \par \uc2  Besides introducing new products, they have also opened new offices to strengthen their marketing network. \par \par \uc2  PT Asuransi AIA Indonesia, for example, recently launched two new products offering not only a varying period of premium payment but also emphasizing the savings aspect of the schemes. \par \par \uc2  One of the new products is Provider 88. It offers life insurance coverage, with seven or 21 premium payments until the policyholder reaches 88 years of age. The other product is ARTA 15, which provides 15 years of life insurance coverage with only five years of premium payment. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian-American insurance joint venture director and general manager, Mark S. O'Dell, said the products also presented two benefits, namely an annual bonus and, starting from the second year of the contract, guaranteed cash value every three years. \par \par \uc2  "It's like savings in a bank, but with more benefits," he added. \par \par \uc2  AIA expects that its new insurance schemes will contribute between 35 percent and 45 percent of this year's premium income. \par \par \uc2  Another joint venture company, PT Zurich Life Insurance Indonesia, has also recently launched an innovative product called Zurich Link. \par \par \uc2  The company said the new scheme, which allows customers to set their own investment choice and determine the level of their life insurance protection, would be able to compete with other insurance companies' products. \par \par \uc2  Zurich Life president Ronald A. Cheyne said that the new product offers options for customers to invest in investment funds set in four currencies: the rupiah, pound sterling, U.S. dollar and Australian dollar. \par \par \uc2  Cheyne also said that customers could either put their investment in several currencies or only one, and could withdraw either part or all of it at any time. \par \par \uc2  PT Asuransi Jiwa Bumiputera John Hancock, which entered the individual life insurance market in December 1994, expanded its education savings and advice service to boost its market segment. \par \par \uc2  The company expected that its University Savings Plus would give a further boost to its future premium income. \par \par \uc2  Zurich Life marketing head Handojo G. Kusuma also shared the same optimism that the company's latest product would also receive a good response from the market and contribute greatly to the company's premium earnings. \par \par \uc2  He estimated that the product, targeted at married professionals, would be able to attract 2,000 policyholders by the end of this year. \par \par \uc2  "Amid the tight competition in the life insurance market, there is still a wide gap for Zurich Life to fill," Handojo said. \par \par \uc2  Bumiputera John Hancock president David W. Cottrell said that the company now covered about one percent of the individual insurance market, but believed it would increase in the future. \par \par \uc2  "With our expansion strategy, we are targeting to gain 5 percent of the market by 2002," he said, adding his company has planned to open new branch offices. \par \par \uc2  Angger P. Yuwono, the head of the life division of the insurance council said that the increase in the life insurance market was partly contributed to growing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in society. \par \par \uc2  "Besides, people are turning to life insurance because it also serves as a good investment alternative," Yuwono said. \par \par \uc2  Other insurance experts have also said that the social unrest, which rocked the capital and other parts of the country in May 1997, was one of the factors which contributed to the increase in new policyholders. \par \par \uc2  "The May unrest, which left hundreds of people killed, tells the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  how important it is to have insurance coverage," one analyst said. \par \par \uc2  The growing insurance market has also lured investors to enter the insurance industry. \par \par \uc2  According to the insurance council, at least six life insurance companies were established in 1998 alone, bringing the number of insurance companies in the country to 59, including 23 joint ventures. \par \par \uc2  Yuwono acknowledged that the number of policyholders dropped slightly to 19.58 million in 1998 from 21.5 million in 1997, but he believed that the number of policyholders would jump by about 50 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv96004y4\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
