\par\par \b \uc2  Who's in charge here? \b0\par\par\uc2 859 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 September 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The unexpected turn of events in East Timor has put President B.J. Habibie's political future on the line. Not only is he facing a barrage of criticisms for his administration's failure in preventing violence in East Timor, but he is also coming under strong pressure on the domestic front, including from within his own Cabinet, the military and Golkar Party, as well as his political opponents. \par \par \uc2  This condition partly explains why Jakarta was abuzz with rumors of his impending resignation all day on Wednesday. They only receded after Gen. Wiranto, the minister of defense and security-cum-chief of the Indonesian Military (TNI), denied them later in the day. Habibie appeared to have lost the initiative, at least as far as East Timor \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is concerned. On Tuesday, he declared martial law in East Timor although the proposal, which originated from Wiranto, had been rejected by his own Cabinet and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  a day earlier. Then on Wednesday, he canceled his out-of-town engagements for the next few days, including the summit of the Asia Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation (APEC) forum in Auckland this weekend. \par \par \uc2  Although the rumors of his resignation, or a military take over, have been denied, the events of the past few days left a deep impression that Habibie's wings have been clipped, especially on the question of East Timor. Abroad, he is blamed for the violence in East Timor. At home, he is more criticized for letting the ballot proceed and then consequently losing it. Under an agreement his administration signed with the United Nations, Indonesia will have to let go of the territory which it annexed 23 years ago at a huge cost in terms of lives and money. \par \par \uc2  Essentially, Habibie is being blamed for everything that has happened, and about to happen in East Timor. Politically, the fallout from the East Timor explosion may yet finish him off. Habibie, who stepped into Soeharto's shoes in May last year, has governed the nation with weak legitimacy and with his credibility constantly undermined by his own actions. His chances of retaining the presidency in November must surely be diminished now. East Timor adds to a long list of failures that makes him an unlikely serious presidential candidate. \par \par \uc2  In other cases where he failed - the violence in Ambon and Aceh, the corruption investigation of Soeharto and the Bank Bali scandal to name just a few of the big ones - he relied on the support of Golkar, TNI or the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In facing the East Timor fallout, he is virtually alone. But then, it was Habibie who made East Timor his personal \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  when in January he reversed Indonesia's 23-year \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and offered East Timorese the option of a self-determination vote. This \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  came with little consultation beyond his closest aides. The military and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, two institutions most involved in East Timor, were only brought in at a very late stage of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  discussion. \par \par \uc2  The East Timor reversal \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  won Habibie international acclaims at the time, and it set him apart from his predecessor-and-political mentor Soeharto. His close aides never tirelessly touted East Timor among the breakthroughs that should make him a "reformist". If it was not for the violence which erupted in East Timor after the Aug. 30 ballot, his international standing would surely rise, and this, in turn, would boost his chances in the November presidential election. Alas, this is not the case. East Timor was Habibie's personal gambit which did not pay off. He now has to pay the heavy price. \par \par \uc2  The German-trained aircraft engineer naively overestimated his own power, and underestimated the institutions around him that could provide him with the political support. When he offered East Timorese the chance to determine their own future, he overlooked the constitutional process: such a decision must come from the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR). He failed to foresee the strong resistance from within the military against his decision to let the ballot in East Timor, and to risk losing the territory for which many soldiers gave up their lives. Habibie is no Soeharto, who almost always had his way because he controlled the MPR and the military. \par \par \uc2  Now politicians of all colors are only too happy to seize the opportunity to attack Habibie, even as he faces a grave crisis with all the international criticisms over East Timor. The Golkar Party is expected to review its nomination of Habibie as its presidential candidate. It would surprise no one if cabinet members began keeping their distance from him. His presidential accountability report must also stand little chance of being accepted by the MPR in November. \par \par \uc2  Habibie's days are virtually numbered. Even if he remains in charge of the government until November, he will find the going even rougher as he will rule with even less credibility than he had before. Whatever happens now, Indonesia is entering a new period of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , with the disturbing question: Who is really in charge of the country now? \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv9a004oj\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'Corporate restructuring must take workers into account'. \b0\par\par\uc2 254 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 September 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The government must initiate approaches that favor workers in restructuring crisis-hit companies, said senior ILO official Max Iacono. \par \par \uc2  He said the ILO is currently setting up a team on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery that is 'friendly' to workers. \par \par \uc2  "The strategy is to provide opportunities to those who have been laid off, " said Iacono in a seminar here on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  Iacono said the study on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis is wide-ranging and involves many business sectors. \par \par \uc2  "The study is now finished, but must be finalized and analyzed and discussed with the government and related bodies such as companies and labor organizations." \par \par \uc2  Sectors targeted by the study include banking, finances, manufacturing and agribusiness as well as small and medium businesses. \par \par \uc2  Every sector has its particulars in terms of labor matters, said Iacono. \par \par \uc2  "It's hard to make one general conclusion over labor matters." \par \par \uc2  On small and medium businesses that absorb many workers, Iacono called on the government "to create a conducive business climate in support of consistent rules and policies and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  breaks." \par \par \uc2  "There must also be simple credits schemes. ILO still finds such schemes offered in a disorderly manner," said Iacono. \par \par \uc2  According to Yusmaliani of LIPI, external factors such as expensive imported raw materials, low purchasing power lead to a feeling of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  among companies. \par \par \uc2  "Small and medium companies should fare better in facing these problems, as they are more flexible in adapt themselves to a changing environment," said Yusmaliani on the same occasion. (msw). \par \par \u