\par\par \b \uc2  Parties rethink state security bill. \b0\par\par\uc2 592 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 September 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Officials of the country's top political parties signaled on Sunday they were leaning toward delaying the endorsement of the government-sponsored state security bill by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Golkar deputy chairman Marzuki Darusman told The Jakarta Post that broader concerns were a greater priority than the fiercely opposed bill. \par \par \uc2  "We need to consider the general good and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion," he said of the bill which has sparked nationwide street protests and opposition. \par \par \uc2  Critics charge the bill, which covers measures permitted during states of emergency, would grant overwhelming authority on the military which could be misused to quash opposition and curb freedom of the press. \par \par \uc2  The bill is in its final stages of deliberation and is due for endorsement at a plenary session of the House on Thursday, one day before the current group of legislators ends its term of office. \par \par \uc2  The sudden about-face came after top officials from several parties - Golkar, the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI Perjuangan), the National Mandate Party (PAN) and National Awakening Party (PKB) - met on Sunday evening. \par \par \uc2  The meeting was facilitated by editors from several mainstream publications. \par \par \uc2  Marzuki said there was an agreement among the parties on "the possibility of delaying the bill until the new House convenes". \par \par \uc2  "On Monday we will summon Agus Muhyidin and also discuss if the bill is undemocratic or limits democracy itself," Marzuki said of Golkar's next move. \par \par \uc2  Golkar legislator Agus heads the House's special committee deliberating the bill. \par \par \uc2  Marzuki acknowledged that there was a prevailing fear that the bill, once endorsed, would be used to call off the General Session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) in November. \par \par \uc2  Among the MPR's primary tasks will be to adopt the guidelines of state \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and elect a new president. \par \par \uc2  Bara Hasibuan of PAN, who also attended Sunday's meeting, confirmed that a general consensus was reached on the possibility of delaying the bill's endorsement. \par \par \uc2  He contended that pushing the bill into law against widespread opposition would only aggravate the already fragile political climate. \par \par \uc2  "It will ignite a process of radicalization," he told the Post. \par \par \uc2  Election \par \par \uc2  Asked if the meeting discussed the possibility of moving forward the date of the General Session, Marzuki responded that there was a growing understanding that the Assembly could expedite the presidential accountability and election. \par \par \uc2  "There's no need to wait until November," he said. \par \par \uc2  "If we wait until November, it will only prolong the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  which could result in a deepening of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis." \par \par \uc2  Bara also remarked that the country was in a state of crisis due to the lack of leadership shown by President B.J. Habibie. \par \par \uc2  He said that customary issues tackled by the Assembly could be put on the back burner of priorities given the pressing need for a new government to reinvigorate the nation. \par \par \uc2  "So it is better to speed up the election of a new president, rather than focusing on things such as the guidelines of state \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  or amending the 1945 Constitution," he said. \par \par \uc2  The first phase of the Assembly begins on Oct. 1 with the inauguration of new members. \par \par \uc2  Signs that parties were working together were evident on Saturday evening when six parties - Golkar, the United Development Party (PPP), PKB, PAN, the Crescent Star Party (PBB) and the Justice Party (PK) - agreed to form a small team to prepare rules of procedures for the upcoming MPR session. \par \par \uc2  The team is expected to submit its recommendations on Sept. 25. (05) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv9k0053f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
