\par\par \b \uc2  Pension funds stay with banks. \b0\par\par\uc2 488 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 September 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The country's pension funds continue to put most of their money in bank deposits despite the sharp drop in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , investment analysts said. \par \par \uc2  Director of PT Citicorp Securities Indonesia Rizka Baely said on Wednesday that about 90 percent of the total Rp 20 trillion (about US$2.35 billion) in pension funds was deposited in banks. \par \par \uc2  "Only about 10 percent of their money is put in stocks and bonds." \par \par \uc2  He said the unbalanced investment reflected the investment fund managers' worries about the country's portfolio investment climate. \par \par \uc2  Most of the managers are taking a "safety first" approach in facing the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said, adding that the strategy was out of the question at more stable times. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which peaked at 70 percent in July last year in conjunction with the government's tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to ease high inflation pressures, have gradually decreased in recent months. The rate on the three-month deposit, for example, has returned to the precrisis level of about 13 percent to 14 percent per annum. \par \par \uc2  Rizka said that investing in the stock market should theoretically yield higher returns than putting money in banks because most of the shares were undervalued. \par \par \uc2  Senior economist Syahrir agreed that it was now time to enter the stock market because many shares were already undervalued, especially those in the consumer goods sector and ones that are export-oriented. \par \par \uc2  He advised pension funds to enter the market now and hold their investment at least until after the presidential election in November. \par \par \uc2  He said the strategy would give them higher yields than the 13 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  currently offered by domestic banks. \par \par \uc2  Syahrir, president of PT Syahrir Securities, based his stock market prediction on a turnaround in the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators. \par \par \uc2  He said that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year was projected to be minus 1 percent, compared to minus 13.7 percent last year. \par \par \uc2  The inflation rate, which reached as high as 77.6 percent for the whole of 1998, has continued to decline since early last year. But it has been in negative territory since March; August's inflation was minus 0.93 percent, compared to minus 1.05 percent and minus 0.34 percent in July and June. \par \par \uc2  Syahrir also predicted that the rupiah would strengthen against the greenback at the end of the year. He said that anticipation of a stronger rupiah would fuel positive sentiment on the local stock market. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors, he added, would interpret a strengthening of the rupiah in the near future as a message to enter the stock market. \par \par \uc2  Syahrir said that investors should stay away from property shares because the recovery of most companies in the sector was not predicted in the near term. \par \par \uc2  "I don't recommend that anybody invest in the property sector until at least another five years from now," he said. (udi) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv9u005mq\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
