\par\par \b \uc2  Prospects for RI's recovery. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,208 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 October 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following article is taken from a presentation at the Indonesia Next: Politics, Business and The Impact of Change Conference in Bali on Friday. \par \par \uc2  By Mar'ie Muhammad \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): After a long political struggle, the People's Consultative Assembly succeeded in electing Abdurrahman Wahid as the fourth president of the Republic of Indonesia, the third largest democratic country. \par \par \uc2  A milestone has been laid for a long, arduous journey. Now society is in waiting, generally with mixed feelings and opinions. The core of the issue, a formidable task to resolve, is restoring confidence. For this we need urgently to build a credible government, fully committed to the reform program, including to rebuild good governance. \par \par \uc2  It is obvious that the government, in collaboration with civil society, has to reunite Indonesia's highly fragmented society. Furthermore, it is the duty of the nation to restore trust in society as a main social element that has continued to deteriorate. \par \par \uc2  Restoration of peace and order should become the first priority of the new government, with active support from all citizens. The government should secure strong support from political parties, professionals, civil society and the regions, and should be welcomed by the international community. \par \par \uc2  To achieve this objective, the new Cabinet should be a sort of grand coalition which is able to accommodate various interest groups, including the minorities. \par \par \uc2  While other regional economies have begun to recover from the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, Indonesia's recovery has occurred at a slower pace. Thailand, for example, is expected to attain a real gross domestic product growth rate of 3 percent to 4 percent, and the Korean \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to grow by more than 5 percent. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia, in contrast, is unlikely to achieve a 1.5 percent to 2 percent increase in real GDP. \par \par \uc2  However, it should not be forgotten that the greater severity of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in Indonesia compared to other regional economies is at its root a reflection of political instability, a devastated and dysfunctional banking sector, a deeply indebted corporate sector and pervasive corruption. \par \par \uc2  Some signals of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery are quite encouraging. One is inflation with an annual rate falling to less than 6 percent in August. The one-month interest rate has dropped below 13 percent per annum. The rupiah has strengthened to about 7,000 to the U.S. dollar although it is still highly volatile. \par \par \uc2  Share prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange rose by 120 percent between October 1998 and June 1999 and are still more than 80 percent above their level of a year ago. \par \par \uc2  This said, I still do not mean to belittle the magnitude of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  difficulties that we face. The bank restructuring program, for example, has made enormous progress, with insolvent banks having been closed, most remaining banks recapitalized and much of the bad debt moved to an asset management agency. \par \par \uc2  Nonetheless, our banking system remains dysfunctional. Although banks continue to perform one of their two critical functions - absorbing savings from households and businesses - they are not performing the other function, which is to channel these savings into productive investments in the real \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Bank lending is still at a standstill and is unlikely to recover anytime soon. Similarly, some progress has been made in corporate debt restructuring. More than 280 companies with over US$23 billion in outstanding foreign debts have begun negotiations under a program supported by the World Bank, and 27 of these debtors have reached agreements in principal involving more than $3 billion. \par \par \uc2  However, most corporate debt is still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the Indonesian bankruptcy law and its enforcement are still weak. The bank restructuring agency has taken about Rp 230 trillion of bad debt but very little of this has been successfully restructured. In this regard, it is critical to strengthen the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) and its operations, and for this IBRA needs strong political support. Until the banking and corporate debt problems are resolved, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery will remain anemic. \par \par \uc2  Another obstacle that Indonesia will face over the next few years will be the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden created by the crisis. Before the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, Indonesia did not have a significant \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  problem. In fact, the government had been running surpluses for several years. The crisis created enormous new \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  obligations for social safety nets, food and energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and most importantly the enormous cost of financial sector restructuring. At the same time, with the slowdown in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, domestic revenue as a share of GDP declined. \par \par \uc2  Consequently, Indonesia is expected to experience a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 4 percent to 5 percent of GDP during the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. For the time being these \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits are being financed by foreign borrowing but this is obviously not a viable long-run solution. The government's foreign debt has already risen by more than $15 billion during the crisis, creating a larger burden on future generations, and the willingness of the international community to provide official assistance to Indonesia will diminish with time. \par \par \uc2  While the soundness of future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  cannot be guaranteed simply on the basis of past performance, there are several reasons to believe that the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  difficulties can be overcome. First, there is considerable scope for raising \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue. In recent years Indonesia's non-oil \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts have amounted to only 10 percent to 12 percent of GDP. \par \par \uc2  This is far less than the share of GDP collected in other economies. Thailand and the Philippines, for example, collect more than 15 percent of GDP in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue. Second, there is some scope for reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly with respect to fuel and energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , although removing these \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be painful. \par \par \uc2  Third, the government has acquired a great number of valuable assets as a consequence of the financial sector restructuring program. These assets, including some of the largest private banks and industrial companies, will be sold back to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the next few years, creating an income stream to offset the cost of bank restructuring. Government banks and state-owned enterprises will also be privatized over the next few years. \par \par \uc2  Of course, the government's political will to divest these assets in a fair and transparent manner must remain firm. Maintaining firm political support for this process is highly essential, particularly if the participation of foreign investors is needed. \par \par \uc2  In sum, where do we go from here? \par \par \uc2  * Equitable development through pro-poor \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and empowerment of the small scale business. \par \par \uc2  * Export-led growth, push for foreign investment and continuous deregulation. \par \par \uc2  * Sale of banks and other IBRA assets and the privatization of state-owned enterprises. \par \par \uc2  * Monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that focuses on attaining and keeping low inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  * A neutral and more effective \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection system. \par \par \uc2  We can only realize the above agenda with the support of the international community, including international financial institutions. We firmly believe that democracy is an essential foundation for the establishment of a more favorable nation that is capable of carrying out fair and transparent activities in all aspects of society. Maintaining international support for Indonesia is highly critical, based on mutual interest and respect. \par \par \uc2  The author is a former finance minister and a founder of the private Indonesian Transparency Society. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvan006hj\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
