\par\par \b \uc2  Raising revenue without  \highlight22\uc2 tax \highlight\uc2  hikes. \b0\par\par\uc2  By J. S. Uppal and Sukanto Reksohadrodjo \par \uc2 1,642 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 October 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  YOGYAKARTA (JP): Now that the nation has completed the momentous task of democratically electing the national assemblies, the President and vice president, it has to face the stark reality of the massive social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems facing the country. Among several difficult tasks for the new administration, the priority is to raise sufficient government revenue to cover mounting \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  needed to deal with the nation's problems. \par \par \uc2  During previous years, with high oil prices and the influx of massive foreign funds, the government could ignore the problem of high \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits. Now, particularly since the recent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, when oil prices are not as high as before and foreign capital is not as easily forthcoming, the country faces the grim reality of serious shortfalls in domestic revenue. \par \par \uc2  Not before long, the nation will have to stand on her own feet rather than depending on \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  foreign loans. Indonesia's external debt has reached a point where the nation has to sometimes compromise its independence and borrow in order to act on vital issues. Recently, there have been instances where Indonesia had to accept dictates from lending institutions, even when it was clearly not in the national interest. There is a growing feeling among people that too much dependence on foreign aid is robbing Indonesia of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  independence and has made the country a captive state quite easily manipulated by lending institutions. \par \par \uc2  Central government revenues are comprised of oil and gas and non-oil and non-gas earnings. Currently (1998-99) 75 percent of total non-oil non-gas revenues come from \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The two major \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  are income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , both individual and corporate, and Value Added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which contribute 34 and 39 percent of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues respectively. \par \par \uc2  The position of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues in comparison with some neighboring Asian countries can be seen from the following table: \par \par \uc2  Table: Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Revenues Compared with Neighboring Asian Countries \par \par \uc2  (Percent of GDP) \par \par \uc2  Indonesia: Total \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Revenues (12.0), Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (4.8), Value Added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (3.2); Malaysia: Total \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Revenues (20.2), Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (11.5), Value Added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (3.1); Philippines: Total \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Revenues (16.3), Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (9.8), Value Added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (3.89); Thailand: Total \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Revenues (16.9), Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (10.7), Value Added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (7.61); S.Korea: Total \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Revenues (17.10), Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (6.3), Value Added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (5.3). \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rates (Initial and Maximum) \par \par \uc2  Indonesia: Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (10.30), Value Addes \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (10); Malaysia: Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (5.40), Value Addes \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (NA); Philippines: Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (10.35), Value Addes \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (NA); Thailand: Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (5.45), Value Addes \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (15.00); S.Korea: Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (10.50), Value Addes \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (10.16); \par \par \uc2  Note: Calculated from various sources. These figures should be used for illustrative purposes only. Due to differences in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  coverage and periods, these figures are not strictly comparable. \par \par \uc2  Why does Indonesia lag behind her Asian neighbors in collecting \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues (called \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Effort)? It is not that Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates are so high they would discourage taxpayers and investors. In fact \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates in Indonesia are in general comparatively lower, as figures in the above table show. It should be noted that these are legal or nominal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates. If we take real or effective \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates (\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  actually paid as a percent of taxpayers total income), these figures become much lower. \par \par \uc2  To cite the case of income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while the top \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 /nominal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate is 30 percent, in real terms, we have estimated that it is not more than 20 percent. It just means that high income earners do not bear the legally mandated burden of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  While statistical, information on the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden of different income classes is not available, one could infer that the biggest burden falls on the middle and lower classes, particularly in the case of the VAT. \par \par \uc2  How do we account for this unfortunate situation? There are two explanations. Firstly, in Indonesia only a small proportion of the population is liable for \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is estimated that between 85 to 90 percent of people in this country do not fall within the income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  net as most of them have incomes below the income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  threshold. \par \par \uc2  The unfortunate part is that less than 1 million people, or less than one half of one percent of the total population, are even registered for filing \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns. To make the situation worse, from this small amount of registered taxpayers, only 55 percent even care to file \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns. \par \par \uc2  Also, there are huge \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  arrears to be collected. For income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  alone, Rp 6.236 billion was delinquent in 1997-98, which constitutes 17 percent of the total \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collectible. The rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  delinquency has increased in the recent times. This is massive \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evasion indeed, which if not stopped, will make Indonesian income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ineffective. \par \par \uc2  Secondly, there is the problem of many \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  loopholes used by individuals and corporations to reduce their \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  liability. Interestingly, when the existing income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and VAT were introduced during 1985-86, there were only a few exemptions and deductions. The filing of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  was made voluntary, assuming honesty on the part of the taxpayer. There was also a stipulation of strict \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  law enforcement through intensive audits. It is pertinent to cite the potential effects of proper audits. \par \par \uc2  In June 1986, an independent task force of auditors consisting largely of returnees from overseas training programs and reporting directly to the Director General of \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  launched a special audit on two dozen companies reporting zero or negative \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  liability. These firms were assessed to owe Rp 87 billion in \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , fines and penalties. While this audit campaign cost only Rp 250 million, it yielded a direct return of that was 340 times the investment. \par \par \uc2  Later on, several loopholes were introduced. There were two reasons for this. Firstly the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  department could not cope with the need for intensive audits of large numbers of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns found to be in non-compliance with the voluntary \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws. Rather than strict enforcement of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  thorough audits, an easy way out was adopted, by introducing a final withholding system of various items of income which of course suited the upper income class taxpayers. If you look at the list of final \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  withholdings, some of the items are bizarre: unheard of in countries with reasonable \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  systems. \par \par \uc2  For example if an employee has one job, there is a final withholding of say 15 percent, no matter what his other sources of income - interest, dividends or rents - may be. The interesting part is that government pays the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  for government employees. In this way, one can make a fortune with just one job and pay no \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  at all. \par \par \uc2  One can become super rich from other income sources such as interest on deposits, stock dividends, rents and royalties, with \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  liability of only 15 percent as the final withholding taxalthough if the total income of this \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  payer was put together, he may well be in the 30 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  bracket. These are only a few examples of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  abuse. \par \par \uc2  There are several others showing how these \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  loopholes have seriously eroded the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  System and have made a mess of it, as is the case with VAT which has also lost much of its steam from various changes introduced since 1986 to lessen the workload in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  department and to please vested interests. Indonesian VAT has lost its special feature of being a "Money Machine" as originally stipulated. \par \par \uc2  Fortunately, however, as a silver lining in the otherwise dark clouds hovering over the Indonesian skies, there exists a big, untapped potential in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system. Even with the existing legal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates, the government can raise needed \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues by following a two-pronged strategy: to make modifications in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws to reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  loopholes which have reduced \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues and diminished \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  equity. \par \par \uc2  Secondly, the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration needs to be strengthened to enforce proper \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  compliance. It suffers from a lack of coordination between different agencies, for example between the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and excise and customs departments. Also the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  department lacks much needed independence to interpret and enforce \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws without any outside interference. \par \par \uc2  The legal setup of the American Internal Revenue System would be a good case study to make the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  department independent of any politically motivated intervention in enforcing the collection of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  liability, particularly from the politically and economically powerful classes. Consider the independence and power vested in the American \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  agency: the Internal Revenue System. There are recent well-known instances where IRS did not even spare the President and Vice President of the United States from accusing them of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  irregularities. \par \par \uc2  The idea of making \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  agencies independent, though common in Western developed countries, is being increasingly adopted in other elsewhere to deal with the serious problem of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  abuse by powerful people. It may also be prudent to invest funds to update computer technology in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  department to develop an elaborate \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  database so that no item of income received by any taxpayer escapes the eyes of the collectors. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia does not need to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates. Merely by removing the abuse of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  loopholes and illegal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evasion practices, the government can collect sufficient \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues to decrease the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits and to run the nation. \par \par \uc2  Dr. J. S. Uppal and Dr. Sukanto Reksohadrodjo are professors of economics at the State University of New York at Albany, New York, USA and Gadjah Mada University, Yogyakarta, Indonesia. This article is a part of their continuing research on \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Reform in Indonesia under the USAID-funded project, Sustainable Indonesian Growth Alliance, based at Gadjah Mada University, Yogyakarta. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvar0069b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
