\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Budget \highlight\uc2  restraints. \b0\par\par\uc2 694 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 November 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The decision by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Tuesday to release the PricewaterhouseCoopers full audit on Bank Bali will pave the way for the resumption of US$4.7 billion in international aid held up since September, thereby securing state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues for the second half of the 1999/2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year ending in March. \par \par \uc2  The aid suspension, prompted by the politically charged scandal, has unnerved the market for fear that the government might resort to printing money to plug its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  hole or cutting fuel or electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the risk of triggering social and political instability. The long-awaited publishing of the report also enables the government to start negotiating a new set of reform programs with the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which is heading the $43 billion bailout for Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Securing state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  financing is quite crucial, especially now when only \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  can provide the badly needed \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  to get market demand growing as most businesses, deprived of working capital loans as an impact of the crippled banking sector, are operating far below designed capacities. \par \par \uc2  But since \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues will likely remain slack due to the slower than expected recovery of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and it will take some time before new investment takes place even though the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been resolved after the installment of a new government with full legitimacy, foreign aid will continue to play a major role in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , at least until 2001 when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to pick up at a much faster rate. \par \par \uc2  One should not read too much into a recent statement by the new finance minister, Bambang Sudibyo, that the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  posted a surplus of Rp 17 trillion during the first half (April to September) as a result of the steep rise in international oil prices. What Bambang seemed to calculate was simply a surplus on a provisional cash-flow basis, failing to take into account lower than expected revenues to be raised from the privatization of state companies and by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA). Moreover, the higher oil prices will double fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Rp 20 trillion and raise electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to more than Rp 10 trillion from a mere Rp 2 trillion last \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  The new minister for investment and state enterprises, Laksamana Sukardi, disclosed on Monday that the $1.5 billion revenue target set for privatization of state enterprises would not likely be achieved. IBRA, which has been demoralized by the Bank Bali scandal since it was revealed in July, has been able to raise only about Rp 8 trillion of the Rp 17 trillion it was tasked to collect. \par \par \uc2  Planning for the next \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  starting in April will be more daunting as domestic debt service payments alone, imposed by the issuance of about Rp 600 trillion in treasury bonds to finance bank restructuring and recapitalization, could reach as high as Rp 50 trillion, compared to Rp 34 trillion in the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  Since the $4.2 billion in foreign debts rescheduled last year under the Paris Club covered only loans due to mature in March, government foreign debt service burdens will increase again next \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. Without another rescheduling agreement for at least $6 billion in debts due within the next two years, the government could suffer an unsustainable, explosive \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Hopefully, with better cooperation with the IMF, the high legitimacy of the new government would pave the way for debt rescheduling negotiations with Paris Club creditors. But even with another foreign debt rescheduling, the next state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will still see a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , though not likely as high as 5.8 percent of gross domestic product estimated for the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  The government simply has no leeway for tightening the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  too quickly, not only because of ballooning \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and debt service burdens. It is also because the government is the only sector that can right now generate a \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  until domestic and foreign investment resumes after the removal of political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The main challenge is how to balance the objectives of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvb3006rl\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
