\par\par \b \uc2  The need for a viable opposition. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Baladas Ghoshal. \par \uc2 1,266 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 November 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The drama that began to unfold in Indonesia with the disgraced resignation of Soeharto has now reached another stage with yet another disgraced exit - of B.J. Habibie - and the election of Abdurrahman Wahid, popularly known as Gus Dur, and Megawati Soekarnoputri as well as the composition of the new Cabinet. \par \par \uc2  The outcome is a mixture of surprise, hope, anxiety, disappointment, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and even disbelief. \par \par \uc2  It was obviously a surprise because none of the analysts or the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion polls had ever predicted Abdurrahman emerging as the eventual President. \par \par \uc2  Opinion polls had veered more toward Megawati, or if she failed because of her inability to cut deals with other political groups, Habibie was viewed as the likely winner. \par \par \uc2  It has also aroused hope in the sense that although the combination of Abdurrahman and Megawati may not have been an ideal combination - both appear to be solidarity-makers and lack real administrative experience - they unquestionably were the most acceptable of the available options. \par \par \uc2  More importantly, Abdurrahman so far has been able to bring in a new style of functioning by curtailing the role of the military and establishing civilian supremacy in decision-making. He has also been creating a new mind-set with the abolition of two ministries which were perceived to be a reflection of the ancien regime. \par \par \uc2  At the same time, the outcome has brought into sharp focus the essential contradictions in Indonesia's political environment - the gap between the aspirations of ordinary people reflected in the general election and the elite's inclination to manipulate events and issues to impose their preferences on ordinary people. \par \par \uc2  From the perspective of political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability, such engineering on the part of the elite may at times be expedient, but may not be desirable from the point of electoral politics and democratic norms. The eventual outcome of the election of the two top positions and the composition of the Cabinet has made the electoral process practically irrelevant. \par \par \uc2  Unless this anomaly is removed through a constitutional amendment by the time the next election takes place, people will generally lose their faith in the elections and eventually in the democratic process, however successful the present government might be in their tasks. \par \par \uc2  The outcome has created \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and anxiety from another perspective - the absence of an effective viable opposition in the legislature, an essential element in the functioning of democracy and for curbing the government from acting arbitrarily and abusing its powers. There is nothing wrong in a national reconciliation government trying to bring about consensus on certain basic national values, and to crafting a common minimum program to serve the interests of the people and hence good governance. \par \par \uc2  In fact this is one of the crying needs of the country, particularly after 32 years of authoritarian rule that created divisions among every section of Indonesian society, leading to suspicion and distrust of each other. Consensus-building is one thing and compromise arising from a weak leadership is another. \par \par \uc2  In fact, there have been instances in history where consensus-building based on the accommodation of various interest groups within the society had brought rich dividends in the form of political stability and societal integration. When India became independent in 1947, the Indian National Congress was the most dominant party because it contributed the most to the freedom of the country. \par \par \uc2  Yet when Jawaharlal Nehru formed his government as the first prime minister of the country, he decided to include quite a few non-Congressmen into his government to reflect various opinions existing within the country. And apart from other objective conditions, this was one of the contributing factors for the stability and national consensus on some of the country's basic values. \par \par \uc2  The other important factors were the role of an alert opposition in the parliament and a vigilant press keeping control over the ruling party's proclivity to act arbitrarily. Even in the worst days of Indira Gandhi's emergency rule, the opposition in the parliament played a significant in the eventual end of her authoritarian rule. \par \par \uc2  In the case of Indonesia, the Cabinet that has been formed is firstly based on compromises and not on consensus. Second, in an attempt to pay back his debt to the political leaders who made his presidency possible, Abdurrahman has practically rewarded most of the top leaders of the important political parties in the legislature leaving practically none for an opposition role. \par \par \uc2  This is all the more critical in view of the character of the political parties in the country which are essentially based on one or two personalities. Once they are removed from the party, it sometimes becomes radar-less, or alternately it may lead to disgruntlement among the elements who missed out on the reward. \par \par \uc2  This will surely have a negative effect on the emergence of a viable opposition in the legislature. Indonesia is already affected by the authoritarian rule under the New Order which had a debilitating effect on civilian institutions as well as on civil society. The recent Cabinet formation may further contribute to the emasculation of an opposition in the legislature. \par \par \uc2  In a normal situation, Golkar should have emerged as the most effective opposition to the new government. But that was not to be, essentially because it was a government-sponsored machine for the mobilization of support for the previous regimes and not a party which normally articulated the interests of the people. \par \par \uc2  Second, Golkar itself is split along many lines over the recent political maneuverings which eventually led to Habibie's downfall. \par \par \uc2  Third, after their induction into the government establishment, there is no single leader left in Golkar who has the capability to function as an effective opposition leader. In the absence of any political party, or a combination of some emerging as the opposition to the new government, one might even think of individual members and interests acting as opposition in the legislature. But the formation of such a group remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and would surely influence the functioning of democracy in the country. \par \par \uc2  The role of an opposition in a democracy is vital. This is more so in view of the past history of Indonesia which practically bred authoritarianism. Both Abdurrahman and Megawati come from a feudal orientation and their positions are no less derived from their family lineage. \par \par \uc2  In such a situation, one can not rule out the possibility of the pair working in a feudal and authoritarian tradition. As a check to that trend, there is a need for an opposition in the legislature. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian media has been very vocal and vigilant in terms of people's interests and aspirations, and will surely play an important role in pressuring the government not to deviate from democratic norms. \par \par \uc2  But that is not enough, and it is not a substitute for an opposition in the legislature which alone can have check government abuses and arbitrary actions. In this sense, the recent outcome may cause some concern to the people who want to lay the foundation of a democracy in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  More important than the absence of a legitimate opposition in the legislature, people's grievances will be automatically brought to the streets by disaffected groups and students who, however, played a historic role in the political transformation of Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  But again, street demonstrations and opposition are not always a preferable alternative to constructive constitutional opposition. \par \par \uc2  The writer is a professor of strategic and security studies at the National University of Malaysia and is an expert on Indonesian politics. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvb4006u3\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
