\par\par \b \uc2  BNI expects recapitalization to start in December 1999. \b0\par\par\uc2 777 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 November 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): A further delay in the recapitalization of publicly listed Bank Negara Indonesia (Bank BNI) might result in a closure of its foreign branches, Widigdo Sukarman, the bank's president, has warned. \par \par \uc2  "We must start the recapitalization program in December, otherwise we risk the closure of our foreign branches," he told reporters on the sidelines of a seminar on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problem on Friday. \par \par \uc2  He said foreign financial authorities, where the bank has its branches, would not tolerate banks to operate with negative capital. \par \par \uc2  BNI has six overseas branches in Singapore, Tokyo, Hong Kong, New York and the Cayman Islands. \par \par \uc2  The government-sponsored recapitalization program is designed to lift the Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) of banks to the 4 percent minimum level. CAR is the ratio between capital and risk weighted assets. \par \par \uc2  Widigdo said the recapitalization program of Bank BNI was delayed due to the country's political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the run-up to the October presidential election, and the outbreak of the Bank Bali scandal in late July. \par \par \uc2  The recapitalization program of the bank was supposed to start in September, in which the government would issue bonds for the bank in three tranches: on Sept. 30, Dec. 31 and March 31, 1999. (Needs to be checked) \par \par \uc2  The International Monetary Fund (IMF) Asia Pacific director, Hubert Neiss, also expressed concern last week over the slow progress of the recapitalization program of state banks. \par \par \uc2  Based on the September 1999 audit result, Bank BNI would need some Rp 52.8 trillion in recapitalization funds to boost its CAR level to 4 percent. \par \par \uc2  Widigdo said the recapitalization funding needs would not further increase because the quality of some of its lending had improved, and the pressure of a negative interest spread had lessened following the sharp drop in domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  BNI launched a rights issue in July to raise funds from \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  shareholders for the recapitalization. \par \par \uc2  The rights issue raised only Rp 238 billion, leaving the government to foot the remainder by injecting bonds. \par \par \uc2  Widigdo said BNI, which is listed on the local stock exchange but still controlled by the state, should start the recapitalization program in December otherwise it would violate the ruling of the capital market supervisory agency on its rights issue. \par \par \uc2  "We must be recapitalized in two months time," he said, without giving further details. \par \par \uc2  The government has helped finance the recapitalization of a few private banks. \par \par \uc2  On state banks, the government has so far only started with the recapitalization of Bank Mandiri, in which the government issued Rp 103 trillion worth of bonds in October after it failed to meet the first deadline in July and second deadline in September. \par \par \uc2  Bank Mandiri needs more than Rp 137 trillion in recapitalization funding. \par \par \uc2  Partner \par \par \uc2  Widigdo said Bank BNI had also offered a chance to German-based Commerzbank to become its strategic partner to further enhance its future operations. \par \par \uc2  "We've talked to Commerzbank about it and they responded positively," he said during the launching of a cooperation with Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM) operator Telkomsel earlier in the day. \par \par \uc2  Nonetheless, he added, the government had so far no plans for BNI's divestment in the near future. \par \par \uc2  Widigdo said Commerzbank belonged to one of the top banks in Germany and as such, BNI would benefit from its expertise and network. \par \par \uc2  Commerzbank, founded in 1870, is one of the three largest private banks in Germany. \par \par \uc2  The bank focuses its business operation in Western Europe and North America and has over 50 outlets in more than 40 countries. \par \par \uc2  Corporate secretary and head of BNI's division for investor relations Sudirman said Commerzbank was not a stranger to BNI as they had cooperated before in the past. \par \par \uc2  In addition, he said, Commerzbank had been BNI's advisor in the fields of asset rehabilitation and risk management since last September. \par \par \uc2  He said aside from advising BNI, Commerzbank would also assist the state-owned bank to implement a business plan that was developed by Arthur Anderson consulting company. \par \par \uc2  "We have a six-month contract with them (Commerzbank) which can be extended if necessary," Sudirman explained. \par \par \uc2  He said Commerzbank had sent its team to work on BNI. \par \par \uc2  "So Commerzbank's people will have the opportunity to evaluate BNI's condition thoroughly and then decide whether they would like to invest in this bank," Sudirman said. \par \par \uc2  Sudirman said the government currently owns some 98 percent of BNI's shares after the bank conducted a rights issue in July. \par \par \uc2  "But they (the government) have yet to inject the funds; so its 98 percent on paper," he explained. (rei/03) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvb800697\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
