\par\par \b \uc2  Foreign investors' concern turns to unrest in Aceh. \b0\par\par\uc2 660 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 November 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the troubled province of Aceh has become a major concern for most foreign investors in Indonesia, according to a Singapore-based economist. \par \par \uc2  Mangal Goswami of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Research Group Asia Pacific said here on Monday the political problem in the oil-rich province would further reduce foreign investor confidence in the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "They take this threat seriously," Goswami said in reference to Aceh's mounting calls for a referendum, which could lead to the separation of the province from Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Speaking at the Cash Management and E-Commerce seminar held by ABN AMRO Bank, Goswami said the key to restoring investor confidence would depend on President Abdurrahman Wahid's handling of the Aceh issue. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors would like to see the government use peaceful means in dealing with the Acehnese, Goswami said, adding that opening up a dialog was crucial for positive developments. \par \par \uc2  He said foreign investors feared that if the Aceh problem could not be resolved properly it would spark further social instability in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Goswami did not specify whether foreign investors expected Indonesia to disintegrate should Aceh separate from Jakarta, but added that "\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability hinges on political and social stability". \par \par \uc2  He said that even before the Aceh issue investors had delayed channeling funds into Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Goswami said investor caution was related to a wait-and-see attitude on the performance of the newly established government. \par \par \uc2  He said the fundamental soundness of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was of even greater importance than the Aceh issue. \par \par \uc2  He said investors were generally upbeat about Indonesia's prospects and had expressed their intention of returning to the country. \par \par \uc2  Goswami said investor confidence had been boosted by diminished political risks and the election of a President who had a grasp of Indonesia's key problems. \par \par \uc2  "Investors have switched the question from whether they would invest in Indonesia to when they would invest," he said. \par \par \uc2  Goswami projected that starting from next year foreign investments would gradually pick up, but that any improvement was dependent on resolution of the Aceh issue. \par \par \uc2  In regard to Indonesia's overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook, he said that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery would largely depend on the combination of foreign direct investment and restructuring of the banking sector. \par \par \uc2  He said investors would place their funds in export-oriented sectors, and cited the textile and shoe industry as lucrative opportunities. \par \par \uc2  He said the agriculture sector, which has reaped huge profits during the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, did not hold huge appeal for foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  Goswami was optimistic that exports would rise sharply, not only because of foreign investment flows but also due to a stronger demand for Indonesian products. \par \par \uc2  In the financial sector, he predicted banking \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to further decline to about 11 percent by early next year, from the current 13 percent. \par \par \uc2  "It's normal that \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  drop sharply after a crisis," he said, but added that he expected \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to slowly climb after bottoming out at 11 percent or 12 percent. \par \par \uc2  He projected that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would then attain their pre-crisis level. \par \par \uc2  Separately, ABN AMRO Bank country manager Pieter Van den Akker said foreign investment was vital in reviving Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Akker declined to confirm talks on ABN AMRO's intention to acquire several Indonesian banks. \par \par \uc2  He said Indonesia's banking crisis was unprecedented in history, describing the cost for restructuring the banking sector as "phenomenal". \par \par \uc2  He said bank's loan portfolios had generally been negative but that he expected the situation to change so that such loans would start to pay interest again. \par \par \uc2  ABN AMRO's role in attracting foreign investment would be as a source of information to investors regarding Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said, adding that ABN AMRO was the oldest foreign bank in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Akker said that with its global network, the bank would also provide trade financing to boost Indonesian exports. (03) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvbg006u7\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
