\par\par \b \uc2  Urgent  \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy \highlight\uc2  tasks for RI. \b0\par\par\uc2  By J. S. Uppal and Sukanto Reksohadiprodjo \par \uc2 1,076 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 November 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  YOGYAKARTA (JP): The revival of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from its recent crisis will depend on whether the government takes immediate and important steps to deal with the crucial \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues highlighted in this article. Any further neglect will be harmful for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability and financial sustainability. \par \par \uc2  Economists sometimes make budgets sound technical, using theoretical jargon. Governments often use different accounting tricks to make them politically acceptable. \par \par \uc2  The term used to describe the latter way to present a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is called "\b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  trickery", and the government of Indonesia has been doing exactly that for many years. While the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been clearly in the red, it has been presented to the nation as a balanced \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as per constitutional requirements. \par \par \uc2  Rather than simply taking the difference between domestically raised resources from \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and oil/gas revenues and total government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a true indication of the budgetary condition - surplus or \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  - the government covers up the actual yearly \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  by ever-increasing foreign borrowing. \par \par \uc2  As a cash flow device this may be justified, but it also reflects the reality of the government's chronic inability to raise sufficient domestic revenues to meet its \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  While the magnitude of the real \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  depends on how one calculates and presents it - there are different figures ranging from 4.5 percent to 7.5 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) - there is no denying the fact that the nation is in a state of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  distress. \par \par \uc2  The government revenues, particularly \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  yields, are lagging seriously behind mounting government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the nation is increasingly dependent on foreign borrowing to make ends meet. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system is riddled with many \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  loopholes designed ostensibly for administrative purposes, but really to benefit upper-income people. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system has thus been seriously eroded. The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  base has been narrowed further by massive \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evasion through concealing incomes through noncompliance. \par \par \uc2  We discussed the sad state of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  in an article in The Jakarta Post on Oct. 27. Suffice to say here only 1 percent of our population is even registered as income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  payers, and only about half of them even care to file \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns for paying income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  based on voluntary compliance. \par \par \uc2  A massive amount of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  liability stands uncollected and the rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  delinquency has recently increased. Value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (VAT), dubbed the "money machine" due to its high revenue potential, has lost much of its steam as a result of changes introduced after lobbying by businesspeople. \par \par \uc2  Against this shortfall in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue, government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to increase. Without drastic cuts in routine and development \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  on basic goods introduced to help the poor, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlays will continue to grow. \par \par \uc2  Since the recent popularly-elected government has been espousing the cause of poor and needy, it cannot easily reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  or trim down the size of the government work force to reduce government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  This means that unless the government raises \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues by a substantial amount, it will continue to face serious \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  distress with a continuing dependence on foreign borrowing. \par \par \uc2  There is a serious need for the nation to ponder over this vital question. How long and how much can it depend on capricious and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  foreign borrowing just to keep its government running? \par \par \uc2  The government should not lose sight of some serious implications of the continuing \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 : inflation, an adverse balance of payments and depreciation of the foreign value of money. All these factors can also lead to the downgrading of the credit rating of the country's bonds and other commercial papers in the world markets. There is an urgent need to restructure the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system and scrutinize thoroughly government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  In a hurried attempt to pacify the demands for autonomy from the provinces on the eve of the last elections, the government passed laws aiming at political and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  decentralization starting in 2001; not too far away from now. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  contains only very broad outlines of the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  relationship between the central and local governments. The sources of self-raised revenues for the local governments have been mostly left undefined. \par \par \uc2  There is a broad provision for 25 percent of the central government resources to be allocated to local governments, without any specific formula for intergovernmental resource distribution. \par \par \uc2  Some resource-rich provinces will be able to claim as much as 80-85 percent of their income from their natural resources. Resource-poor provinces have been assured balanced development, however there is no mention where the resources are going to come from. \par \par \uc2  Most of the central government's present functions, along with its financial resources and personnel, will be transferred to local governments, but no details have been worked out as yet in this respect. \par \par \uc2  People will be able to elect local officials who will raise the people's hopes and expectations for a better life and more control over their local affairs. But they will not know where the necessary resources will come from. \par \par \uc2  In short, in 2001 when the decentralization process will start, Indonesia will find itself in serious financial chaos if all the necessary details are not worked out well in advance. \par \par \uc2  Fortunately, however, Indonesia can benefit from the experience of other federal systems with varying amounts of administrative autonomy. \par \par \uc2  Regions in the United States have a high level of autonomy, so much so that each of the more than 85,000 local governmental units - states, cities, towns, villages, school districts - have their own taxing and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  powers. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, Canada, India, Australia and other democratic federal governments have well-defined and clearly demarcated taxing and \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  powers, vested in different jurisdictions. \par \par \uc2  However, all these federations have a well laid out mechanism for the distribution of central resources amongst local governments. Indonesia can pick and choose from these federations, depending on its region's political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environments. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia should start right away to formulate policies to deal with the forthcoming decentralization. Otherwise, it faces impending chaos. \par \par \uc2  J. S. Uppal Ph.D and Sukanto Reksohadiprodjo Ph.D are professors of economics at the State University of New York, Albany, New York, and Gadjah Mada University, Yogyakarta, respectively. This article is based on their continuing research for the Sustainable Indonesian Growth Alliance, a United States Development Agency (USAID) and Gadjah Mada University Project. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvbi006z2\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
