\par\par \b \uc2  The capital market versus the banking system. \b0\par\par\uc2  By I. Putu Gede Ary Suta \par \uc2 1,342 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 December 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the second of two articles on the capital market and the government's privatization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Some progress has been made in the development of the capital market despite weak government support. Between 1990 and 1997, the Capital Market Supervisory Agency (Bapepam) drafted sophisticated securities regulations that met international standards. Bapepam became one of the most open and transparent of government agencies. However, \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and banking policies were beyond Bapepam's authority and created a barrier to market development. \par \par \uc2  In addition to establishing an honest banking system, we should give priority to a dynamic capital market that will support stable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. A number of measures must be taken: \par \par \uc2  * End Bad Banking: When companies can borrow from banks they control and when state banks supply funds to friends of government officials, it is easier to raise long-term funds by borrowing depositors' money from "friendly banks" than by a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offering of shares. State banks set a bad example and discourage sound banking practices, constituting a barrier to capital market development. \par \par \uc2  The United States has rigorous banking prohibitions against conflict-of-interest transactions, joint-ownership and "interlocking directorates". Except for a \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and development banks, there is no justification for state banks. Government banks, including the banks in the restructuring program, should be privatized with control transferred to parties unaffiliated with borrowers. \par \par \uc2  * Encourage Equity Investment: Because, unlike bank deposits, the government does not guarantee equity investments and because return on equity is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and dependent upon market forces, investors prefer government guaranteed bank deposits, especially when \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are high. Countries intent on developing capital markets provide incentives for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  to use equities for long-term savings. This calls for major \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  changes: \par \par \uc2  * Limit Deposit Guarantees and Bank \b \highlight22\uc2 Interest Rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 : Government guarantees on bank deposits must be limited and subject to interest rate restrictions. Otherwise, the government guarantee creates a "moral hazard" in which weak banks attract money by offering high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while discouraging investment in stocks and long-term bonds. \par \par \uc2  * Postpone \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  for Retirement and Educational Funds: To compensate the risk and long-term nature of equity investments, many governments allow investors to save for retirement or their children's education in funds exempt from current \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  are due only when profits are withdrawn. The country benefits from greater \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability through equity financing. \par \par \uc2  * Encourage \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Companies: Strong incentives are needed to compensate for the cost of distributing equity in an undeveloped market. Some countries stimulate capital market development by lower \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  corporations. For example, a company with capital distributed to 5,000 domestic shareholders might be allowed a reduction on corporate \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , compensated by higher \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on nonpublic companies. To qualify for \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  company must meet disclosure and corporate governance standards. \par \par \uc2  * Make Bapepam Independent: Bapepam has not been able to effectively exercise its enforcement powers because it is not free from political influence. Recent recommendations call for the transformation of Bapepam into an independent agency under the supervision of a board of commissioners, with similar safeguards as the United States' Security and Exchanges. \par \par \uc2  * Accelerate Privatization: The purpose of privatization is not to raise funds for the government, but rather to eliminate an inefficient system that fosters misuse of companies for political benefit. State-owned enterprises are often less efficient than private sector firms and are a drag on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a source of corruption. \par \par \uc2  Despite commitments to the IMF, little progress has been made regarding privatization. Only six state-owned enterprises have sold shares to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and in no case has more than 35 percent of the capital been distributed. There has been no true privatization resulting in transfer of control to the private sector. \par \par \uc2  Vested interests of directors, commissioners, employees and suppliers of state-owned enterprises oppose privatization. State banks and state-owned companies play a key role in the distribution of political favors. \par \par \uc2  Opponents of privatization contend that selling state-owned enterprises is only justified to finance \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. However, many state-owned companies are unmarketable and the others, when profitable, are not easily sold at prices that would significantly help \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  Adversaries of privatization use false nationalism to argue against selling "national assets" to foreigners. They suggest privatization must be postponed until after \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, at which time the idea may be forgotten. \par \par \uc2  The owners of state-owned enterprise are the people of Indonesia, not the government, and certainly not the directors, commissioners and employees. State-owned enterprises were created from \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and it would be logical to return this money as a benefit to taxpayers. \par \par \uc2  Valuation of equities is not exact and is subject to opinion. It is unlikely that there will be consensus as to the "fair value" of shares of state-owned companies. Some other basis must be used. \par \par \uc2  It is possible to devise a system whereby privatization can raise funds to assist the government's finances during the recovery period, while avoiding the political traps of determining a "fair price" or sale to foreigners. This can be done by setting a reasonable price for the sale of shares to taxpayers who would be allowed to purchase some shares of state-owned companies every year and, within limits, use their purchase receipts to pay future \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In effect, the shares would be given to taxpayers who are, after all, the real owners. However, by advancing payment of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  by a number of years, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  would finance the recovery \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Shares of state banks and state-owned securities companies, stores, industrial companies and other ventures that have competitors in the private sector should be entirely divested. Government firms that are uneconomical and have no strategic importance should be liquidated. State-owned companies with strategic importance and without private sector competition may be considered case-by-case. \par \par \uc2  Privatization must include the bank restructuring program that has resulted in the government subscribing to most of the capital of ailing banks. This subscription was accomplished by exchanging government bonds for shares. This program has serious flaws: \par \par \uc2  * Medium and long-term rupiah government bonds are not marketable at current rates in large quantities at a price close to par. Therefore, ailing banks have not received funds to finance recovery. If the bonds were to be sold at true market value - less than par - the banks would be decapitalized and the restructuring program would fail. \par \par \uc2  * The rupiah bonds are medium term with relatively high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This presents a cash flow problem for the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  To solve the problem, it is necessary to recapitalize the banks with bonds that can be resold in very large amounts on the international market. There is no such demand for rupiah bonds, but existing bonds could be substituted with marketable Brady bonds. Brady bonds are a type of government security issued by developing countries in financial difficulty, with a 30-year tenure, guaranteed by 30-year, zero-coupon U.S. Treasury bonds. Brady bonds have the largest international market for sovereign obligations of developing countries. \par \par \uc2  Since payment of the principal is 30 years in the future, and since dollar \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are generally less than equivalent rates in local currency, the Brady bond puts less stress on government budgets than alternative medium-term rupiah financing. By providing restructured banks with Brady bonds, these banks would be capitalized with usable funds and could finance Indonesian businesses and stimulate employment. Restructured banks could become profitable and the increased \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity would improve \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts. \par \par \uc2  Privatization, banking reform and capital market development are linked. The key issue is the introduction of banking reforms prohibiting borrowers from controlling banks and limiting \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  on guaranteed bank deposits. \par \par \uc2  To stimulate the capital market, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives are needed. To remedy defects in the bank restructuring program, ailing banks should be re-privatized and Brady bonds should used as liquid assets for bank recovery. \par \par \uc2  The writer is a former chairman of the Capital Market Supervisory Agency (Bapepam). \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvc9003at\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Bank Putera comes under IBRA - BI supervision remains weak. \b0\par\par\uc2 487 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 December 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The secretary general of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  council (DEN), Sri Mulyani Indrawati, accused \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) of not exercising its control function well over Bank Putera Multikarsa, causing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the bank recapitalization program. \par \par \uc2  "This is a source of concern," Sri said here last week. \par \par \uc2  Sri said if the government recapitalizes banks using trillions of rupiahs "and they are left on their own, when will their CAR ever become positive? We then would have to recap them again. This is worrying." \par \par \uc2  Sri added that the essence of the program is tight BI supervision. \par \par \uc2  "It's still like the time before the crisis. So what is the point of recapitalizing banks if control does not exist? Banks could continue to collapse." \par \par \uc2  She admitted that banking matters are precarious, as attested by the rush on Bank Putera that led to the bank facing liquidity problems. \par \par \uc2  But the swift deterioration of Bank Putera raises BI's capability to control banks. \par \par \uc2  "We have always been concerned over BI's way of monitoring banks. If the banks fall under Category A, they are under BI. If their CAR falls drastically, what then is BI's role?" \par \par \uc2  She said the CAR of Bank Putera - its status is Bank A-would not have dropped drastically if the bank had not non-performance loans (NPLs). \par \par \uc2  "Why was it not specially monitored? How could BI fail to detect the bank's legal lending limit (BMPK) violation?" \par \par \uc2  Last week BI governor Syahril Sabirin said that Bank Putera remains under Category A as it has a positive CAR. \par \par \uc2  Uniquely, IBRA would continue to inject funds to offset the bank's liquidity problems. \par \par \uc2  Finance Minister Bambang Sudibyo has refused to comment on the matter. \par \par \uc2  "Bank Putera is now under IBRA. Please ask IBRA," he told Bisnis last week. \par \par \uc2  IBRA chief Glenn Yusuf has meanwhile said that since Saturday the bank is under IBRA with a status of BDP (banks nursed back to health). \par \par \uc2  "That decision came after five days of discussions with BI and Bank Putera." \par \par \uc2  As of now, Glenn added, the management of Bank Putera will be come under a management team appointed by IBRA. \par \par \uc2  The move falls in line with the government's commitment to protect bank accountholders, including that of Bank Putera. \par \par \uc2  BI's Syahril Sabirin has meanwhile confirmed Bank Putera's status as a status BDP. \par \par \uc2  Bank Putera management team head Masyhud Ali said that despite its BDP status, Bank Putera remains in the hands of its current owners, "unless they plan to let go the bank to the government, in which case it becomes a bank take over [BTO]." \par \par \uc2  Its BDP status, added Masyhud, entitles Bank Putera to earn liquidity assistance that would be put in an escrow account at \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The size of the assistance exceeds the total negative balance of Bank Putera, which is Rp278,5 billion. (dj/ens). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dvcd000sr\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Econit's  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  report. \b0\par\par\uc2 588 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 December 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The government is seen as having lost the momentum to accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery due to a number of factors, two of them being the government \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team's non-independence in dealing with the IMF and the performance of the cabinet which, as a whole, is less convincing. \par \par \uc2  The government's focus in the past two months has been on talks with the IMF concerning the LOI and the new state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (RAPBN), "causing a vacuum which in turn led to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  among investors," said Econit Advisory Group director Rizal Ramli, here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Together with Arif Arryman [direktor of Econit Advisory Group] Rizal yesterday presented Econit's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook 2000 entitiled Year 2000: The rebirth of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The program was opened by Investment and State Firms Development Minister Laksamana Sukardi. \par \par \uc2  Rizal accused the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  of being obsessed with details and technical matters, reducing their ability to take initiatives and manoeuvres. \par \par \uc2  "More ironically, the IMF's commitment remains US$2 billion," said Rizal. \par \par \uc2  IMF's total commitment to rescue Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stands at US$12,1 billion. \par \par \uc2  He said the draft letter of intent (LOI) that would be signed in mid-January 2000 too detailed compared with past LOIs - said to be 100 pages, including annexes and matrixes. \par \par \uc2  IMF's Hubert Neiss is in Jakarta this week to finalize the LOI which would be announced in conjunction with the draft APBN 2000 to the House. \par \par \uc2  Rizal also criticized the cabinet's ability to translate President Abdurrahman Wahid's [Gus Dur] and VP Megawati Soekarnoputri's guidelines. \par \par \uc2  There have been no technical follow-ups from President Gus Dur's foreign visits, and no significant \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies. \par \par \uc2  "The cabinet is a coalition cabinet fraught with compromises, and underscores political considerations rather than professionalism." \par \par \uc2  Rizal dismissed the cabinet as a rudderless "coalition of ducks", marked by lack of coordination and ministers going their own ways." \par \par \uc2  Econit urged "repositioning and reconfiguration" as a mode to address the problem. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery would proceed if "the four engines", namely inflow of private capital, domestic consumption, exports, and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies (APBN) function optimally. \par \par \uc2  The four engines are not performing well, and as such \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery is expected to proceed slowly in the year 2000. \par \par \uc2  On the rupiah, which is suffering from "a waiting game", it will only lead to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery at about 2%. \par \par \uc2  "Potentially, it could be 4%-5%," said Econit. \par \par \uc2  The relatively low figure is below \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  expectation that the new government could expedite \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah will continue to come under pressure next year, though it would ease once private capital flows in. \par \par \uc2  Inflation is expected to be 7%-8% in 2000, higher than this year's due to several factors, namely higher domestic demand, the weak rupiah, fuel price and civil servants salary hike. \par \par \uc2  Econit expects non-oil/gas exports to grow 5% next year, while imports of non-oil/gas items would rise 10%. \par \par \uc2  Banks would only channel credits after the IMF disburses its loans. \par \par \uc2  Econit calls for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  restructuring in order to strengthen the financial sector and encourage the private sector to focus on their core businesses. \par \par \uc2  It also wants to see a tough middle class so that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would withstand any external upheaval. \par \par \uc2  Thirdly, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be made more competitive by reducing negative excesses from conglomeration and the level of industrial concentration. \par \par \uc2  This would accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, increase added-value and prepare better Indonesia in facing rising global competition in the 2000s. (ab). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dvcf000t4\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
