\par\par \b \uc2  The Bank Bali fiasco. \b0\par\par\uc2 792 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 December 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Several analysts and members of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  have welcomed Standard Chartered Plc.'s withdrawal from its Bank Bali investment deal. They argued that the move would open up opportunities for new investors to buy stakes in the bank after its rights issue between Jan. 6 and Jan 12. But the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA), foreign analysts, and most other officials are greatly worried that Standard Chartered's decision will spook foreign investors intending to acquire Indonesian assets. \par \par \uc2  After Standard Chartered's withdrawal, the politically charged scandal, an employee revolt, negative publicity over the past five months and a lawsuit pending at the State Administrative Court, can the Bank Bali name remain attractive as an investment proposition? What is the value of a bank that lacks \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  trust and cooperative employees?. \par \par \uc2  These questions are certainly looming in the Bank Bali rights issue, in which it is hoped that about Rp 4.03 trillion (US$560 million) in recapitalization funds will be raised to elevate the bank's capital adequacy ratio (CAR) to the minimum 4 percent. \par \par \uc2  The Standard Chartered move marks the latest, but surely not the last, episode in the eight-month Bank Bali saga. The saga began in late April as a landmark deal by the first foreign investor willing to stake funds in Indonesia's crippled banking industry. But the deal later developed into a politically charged scandal which implicated several ministers, senior officials and Golkar party leaders. \par \par \uc2  It is true that until the monetary crisis hit Indonesia in August 1997 Bank Bali was rated as one of the best-managed banks in the country, and the only major bank that was not part of a widely diversified conglomerate. But as their capital became negative, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  woes drove all major private and state banks, including Bank Bali, into technical bankruptcy. \par \par \uc2  It is no wonder that when the majority owner - the Rudy Ramli family - experienced difficulties in raising capital to meet the minimum CAR level, six foreign investors, including ABN AMRO, GE Capital and Citibank, expressed an interest in holding a stake in the bank and started negotiations in September, 1998. \par \par \uc2  Standard Chartered, which only joined the negotiations with Bank Bali in late March, was unexpectedly successful in clinching a deal with Rudy Ramli. On April 23 this year, the two signed an agreement that would allow the British bank to have a 20 percent stake in the bank. Negotiations progressed smoothly until Standard Chartered cried foul in July after uncovering during a three-month due diligence, an "improper" Rp 546 billion payment made in early June by Bank Bali. The payment was made to a politically well-connected company as a commission to recover Rp 904 billion in interbank claims from IBRA. \par \par \uc2  The fund scandal immediately escalated into a political scandal and prompted IBRA to pit Bank Bali-embroiled Rudy on one side and IBRA and Standard Chartered on the other in a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -opinion war. Both leveled accusations of improper conduct at each other. More information and documents were leaked regarding the implication of officials and politicians in the scandal, the takeover and the investment and management agreements between IBRA and Standard Chartered. \par \par \uc2  Over time, Rudy built up a broader sympathy base and was perceived by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the victim of a high-level political conspiracy. Most employees who were sympathetic to Rudy revolted in October. In early November, they booted out the Standard Chartered managers from the bank's headquarters. \par \par \uc2  But with Standard Chartered now out of the game, the coast is far from clear for Bank Bali's recapitalization. The bank still carries a potential "land mine" which will deter new foreign investors from buying stocks. The mystery buyer, which accumulated between May and early August through German clearing house Deutsche Boerse almost 40 percent of Bank Bali's shares, remains unidentified, even after the scandal's revelation. \par \par \uc2  The securities commission, Bapepam, which is supposed to conduct an insider trading investigation into the mystery buyer has yet to come up with conclusive results. In a highly questionable statement, the commission recently announced that the 40 percent stockholding was owned by about 1,200 small, independent investors. \par \par \uc2  If the mystery investors and the Rudy Ramli family, which still owns more than 18 percent of the bank, exercise their preemptive rights, IBRA, as a standby buyer of the rights shares, may find it difficult to quickly sell its shares as planned because new investors will not be assured of management control. \par \par \uc2  Given this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Bank Bali's battered condition, we would not be surprised if the next episode of the Bank Bali saga ends with the bank's wholesale nationalization - at the taxpayers' expense. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvck0013v\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI sure rupiah, inflation better next year. \b0\par\par\uc2 304 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 December 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  sees inflation next year under control and the rupiah at 6,000-7,000 per US$. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  deputy governor Miranda S. Goeltom estimated that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would improve next year provided that there are no more political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "\b \highlight22\uc2 Interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are also expected to fall," said Miranda in a discussion Tuesday night. \par \par \uc2  Miranda noted that this week the rupiah has begin to strengthen due to Moody's better ratings over Indonesia and market players' decision not to take positions, \par \par \uc2  "It a complementary situation." \par \par \uc2  Separately, analyst Tjiptono Darmadji said April 2000 would see issuers' financial reports published. \par \par \uc2  "In April activities will be seen, peaking in June2000," he said in a talk show on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Semarang yesterday. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to recover followed by growth as the rupiah stabilizes, and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  near ideal levels. \par \par \uc2  Caution is still needed, he added, as growth remains "artificial", especially the trade surplus as imports have dropped. \par \par \uc2  Balance of payment, said Tjiptono, is favorable as debt repayment has gone down drastically due to restructuring. \par \par \uc2  While \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  have dropped, the market faces problems absorbing credits, he noted. \par \par \uc2  "Be pragmatic and efficient, look at opportunities with a some boldness," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said if the market can take 200,000 cars in 2000, banks should eye only 5% or 10,000 units only. \par \par \uc2  "If one car needs Rp100 million in credits, Rp1 trillion in credits would be channelled." \par \par \uc2  Economist Andreas Lako added that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could potentially be disrupted by political agendas and the threat of national disintegration. \par \par \uc2  However, noted businessman Tengah Herry Moelyanto is upbeat that investments in Central Java would rise "moderately" next year. \par \par \uc2  However, he lamented the poor infrastructure the region has, which he said may hamper exports. (bar/ab/fh). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dvcn000uj\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
