\par\par \b \uc2  Hope amid concerns. \b0\par\par\uc2 663 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 December 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  As the year draws to a close, Indonesians are looking toward the new year - and a dawning new millennium - with justifiable hope. True, a host of problems and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  remain to becloud the new vista of civic liberties that has emerged from under the debris of the collapsed authoritarian and corruption-ridden New Order regime of president Soeharto and its brief extension under president B.J. Habibie. \par \par \uc2  Nevertheless, it cannot be denied that much has been achieved during that span. In the year that is about to elapse, Indonesians passed a major milestone in their 54 years of independence by holding their first truly free general election in more than half a century. \par \par \uc2  As a result, Indonesia now has its first-ever democratically elected President and Vice President leading a government that is committed not only to furthering the cause of democracy, but to eradicating, or at least to laying the groundwork for eradicating once and for all, the country's tangled and expansive web of bureaucratic corruption, collusion and nepotism. \par \par \uc2  As they slowly and falteringly proceed on this new and unfamiliar road, Indonesians are learning that the proper practice of democracy is something that has to be learned. On the one hand, President Abdurrahman's widely published and much resented remark about the national legislature, the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , resembling a "kindergarten" exemplifies his government's dissatisfaction over the quality of debates in the House. \par \par \uc2  Legislators, on the other hand, have on occasion aired their dissatisfaction over the government's performance, which many consider to be moving too slowly and too hesitantly in bringing about the democratic reform demanded by the people. But given the fact that President Abdurrahman Wahid has been in power just a little more than two months, not even the most relentless critic can reasonably deny that much progress has been made in the past year. \par \par \uc2  Unlike previous governments, President Abdurrahman Wahid's Cabinet has so far never been known to disregard criticism, either from the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  or from members of the House. Members of the House, for their part, no longer hesitate to take the initiative in discussing matters of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  import. Steps are being taken to revamp the judiciary and make it independent from the executive. In short, real efforts are being made to implement the principle of trias politica - the separation of powers - in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Achievements aside, the undisputable fact remains that Indonesia continues to struggle under problems that appear almost too big for any government to handle. On the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  front, the government is moving to bring order to the financial ruin left by the corrupt New Order regime. Obviously, given the extent of the devastation, it is a painful effort that will take years - some say, decades - to accomplish. \par \par \uc2  On the social and political fronts the problems are no less daunting. Injustices - physical, social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  - have fed the secessionist sentiments of large sections of the population in several areas, such as Aceh and Irian Jaya, and to a lesser extent in Riau, East Kalimantan and elsewhere. Sectarian violence is disrupting life in several regions, notably Maluku, though on occasion similar cases of unrest flare elsewhere in this country, even in areas close to the capital, Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Little wonder, perhaps, that speculation has been rife lately of a possible return, by whatever means, of the old authoritarian system, which at least on the surface seemed to work in the past. It would be pathetic, of course, if current problems and pressures led Indonesians to so easily forget the lessons of the recent past. It may be true that democracy can be clumsy in operation. Still, it is the only system by which fatal mistakes can be avoided by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  exercising control over policymakers. \par \par \uc2  This being the case, the only appropriate stand for Indonesians to take under the circumstances is to exercise some patience while remaining firmly committed to the ideal of true democratic reform. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dvcv001er\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Fuad urges setting up new  \highlight22\uc2 central bank \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 423 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 January 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Former Finance Minister Fuad Bawazier said the government can always set up a new \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in the wake of a recent audit on BI that showed how rotten it is. \par \par \uc2  Fuad said the state audit body BPK should not hesitate doing an audit on BI covering the 1997-1999 period. \par \par \uc2  "This should be done, never mind the consequences, including the possibility of setting up a new \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There is a legal basis for this, the Philippines did this when President Ferdinand Marcos fell from power," he said in a discussion here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Fuad disclosed that he had always thought that BI was one of the epicenters of the collapse of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "BI could not discharge well its supervisory function," he said. \par \par \uc2  As finance minister, Fuad said, he had assigned IBRA to do an audit on \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  liquidity assistance (BLBI). \par \par \uc2  In May 1998 a report showed that serious violations took place in disbursing, accepting and the use of BLBI. \par \par \uc2  He said funds were taken by managers of banks and channeled to their own business groups. \par \par \uc2  "In fact, owners of banks squeezed their own banks. So it was an artificial rush done through a modus operandi numbering dozens." \par \par \uc2  He said a government ought to help a bank facing a pure rush such as the BCA case, as it was linked to Soeharto's family, and Bank Putera Multikarsa case, which was linked to the Texmaco case. \par \par \uc2  Fuad promised to hand over data to the investigative audit team. \par \par \uc2  "But if the case is not resolved, BI will suffer as they face \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  which could lad to an erosion of foreign confidence." \par \par \uc2  BI, he added, is expected to be cooperative in admitting its weaknesses. \par \par \uc2  Separately, BI Deputy Governor Miranda S. Goeltom called on all parties to think "positively, move forward and dispense with suspicion." \par \par \uc2  "Otherwise, we would hardly be able to move," said Miranda. \par \par \uc2  She said BI hold government bonds worth Rp144.536 trillion in addition to Rp20 trillion, or a total of Rp164.536 trillion. \par \par \uc2  In IBRA's balance, the amount stands at Rp144.536 trillion. \par \par \uc2  "Go ahead, ask IBRA how they plan to recover the funds. We hope they can recover as much as possible," he said. \par \par \uc2  Miranda also hoped that the audit on BI since it became independent on 17 May 1999 up to December 1999 could neutralize the bad publicity over BI. \par \par \uc2  If the audit goes well, the market is likely to react positively. (yn/ab/ens). \par \par \uc2  (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010804dw140000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict