\par\par \b \uc2  Bigger share awaits RI in global textile market - API. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,361 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 January 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The country's textile industry is considered a local giant, providing 19 percent of the country's nonoil and gas revenue and a 1.2 million-strong work force. \par \par \uc2  However, according to the Indonesian Textile Association (API), it accounts for only 2 percent of the global market, which recorded US$350 billion in sales in 1998. \par \par \uc2  In terms of export, the country's textile industry ranked 12th with $7.8 billion in export sales in 1998, compared with top performers China and Hong Kong, which respectively booked $34.7 billion and $31.5 billion in the same year. \par \par \uc2  These figures, nonetheless, suggest there is still plenty of room for the country's textile industry to grow. \par \par \uc2  According to API, the textile industry is the world's third largest after tourism and information technology, which rank first and second respectively. \par \par \uc2  In Indonesia, the industry comprises over 2,300 companies, including 1,700 API members. \par \par \uc2  Among the largest companies are PT Indo-Rama Synthetics, PT Argo Pantes Tbk, PT Apac Centertex Corporation Tbk and PT Texmaco Jaya Tbk. \par \par \uc2  "Analysts say the Indonesian textile industry has no future, but I think they're wrong," API's secretary-general Irwandy Muslim Amin said. \par \par \uc2  Some analysts said the industry would naturally shrink as the income level of Indonesians rises. \par \par \uc2  They said \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would lead to higher wages which the industry could not afford. The industry would thus move to less developed countries with lower wages to maintain competitiveness. \par \par \uc2  Irwandy said a key factor to the growth of the textile industry was population growth. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's large population and heterogeneous income structure are the main factors for the industry to maintain growth, he said. \par \par \uc2  This stands in contrast to the situation of previous textile nations in Europe or Japan, where the fairer distribution of welfare allowed them to simultaneously abandon the textile industry and adopt more technologically advanced industries, he said. \par \par \uc2  Irwandy said in the future, the world's three main textile producers would be developing countries with the largest population. \par \par \uc2  Specifically, the main producers would be China, with its large cotton plantations, India, which is also supported by its cotton plantations and Indonesia, which owns ample resources for producing synthetic fibers. \par \par \uc2  API data said Indonesia's textile exports grew at an annual rate of 5.28 percent between 1993 and 1997, with a total value of $6.4 billion in 1996, $7.3 billion in 1997 and $7.8 billion in 1998. \par \par \uc2  It is estimated that exports could rise to $8 billion this year and to between $12 billion and $20 billion in 2012. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis dealt the first blows to the industry in 1998, a year after it hit. \par \par \uc2  When the crisis struck in mid-1997, the country's textile companies had secured one-year purchase contracts with foreign buyers. This made the industry well-secured in the crisis's first year. \par \par \uc2  However, in 1998, buyers preferred short-term contracts, given the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , causing orders to fluctuate along with the volatile political situation. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis forced domestic demand to drop and caused an oversupply which producers were only able to sell abroad after lowering prices. \par \par \uc2  But the increase in export volume was less than the increase in export revenue, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Maintaining the 1998 export figure for this year will be a challenge," Irwandy said. \par \par \uc2  Among the main buyers of Indonesian textiles in 1998 were the United States with some $1.8 billion, Japan with some $454 million and Germany with about $429 million, the association said. \par \par \uc2  Reform \par \par \uc2  Indonesia faces tight competition with China, Pakistan, India, Thailand and Sri Lanka, with the governments of some countries providing incentives for their textile industries. \par \par \uc2  According to the association, textile producers from Thailand and the Philippines enjoy a four to eight year \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  holiday incentive. \par \par \uc2  This generosity is lacking in the Indonesian government, API said. \par \par \uc2  Irwandy said the industry's main problem is the government. "A lack of attention," was what Irwandy called the government's stance. \par \par \uc2  He said the industry currently needs funding for their working capital and for overhauling its out-of-date machines. \par \par \uc2  However, the government's trade-financing facilities, such as those provided by Bank Export Indonesia (BEI), were deemed insufficient by many textile companies. \par \par \uc2  In addition, many companies are large debtors currently under the supervision of the Indonesian Banking Restructuring Agency (IBRA), a situation which has made it difficult for them to obtain new loans, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Textile producers have machines, laborers, orders and debts," Irwandy said. \par \par \uc2  Of some 800 large textile companies, 134 of them are being taken over by IBRA with a total debt of $7.9 billion, the association reported. \par \par \uc2  He said without debt rescheduling, it would be difficult for producers to import raw material. Hence, production would stop, orders would be unattainable and laborers would face unemployment, he said. \par \par \uc2  In 1998, about 60 percent of the industry's total working capital of $3 billion was spent on imported raw material which included $1 billion for cotton. \par \par \uc2  Irwandy said the government should therefore provide textile companies with the opportunity to obtain loans easier. \par \par \uc2  "We also need capital to replace our old machines," he said. \par \par \uc2  Irwandy said over 80 percent of the industry's machines were over five years old, which has lead to production inefficiencies and lower product quality. \par \par \uc2  For instance, there are about seven million spinning machines, of which 50 percent had to be scrapped due to old age, he said. \par \par \uc2  Data from the association showed that the percentage of synthetic fiber machines above five years old is 78 percent, weaving machines 88 percent, knitting machines 84 percent and garment machines 81 percent. \par \par \uc2  These old machines make it increasingly harder to meet export or even local demand, he said, but added that textile of low quality could still be used for production of clothes for farmers. \par \par \uc2  In the long run, production inefficiency could make Indonesia lose some of its market share to other countries which produce better quality products, he said. \par \par \uc2  However, he added, textile companies could seek alternative funding, for instance from Japanese textile machine producers, which offer credit with low \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Textile producers also blamed the high production costs on corrupt bureaucracy. \par \par \uc2  According to API, the government could cut the industry's production costs by 20 percent, if the government restructured its bureaucracy. \par \par \uc2  The association estimated that various fees for transportation, shipping and port services cost the industry about Rp 300 billion per year. \par \par \uc2  API executive Benny Soetrisno said production costs of Indonesian textile producers ranked second after China in terms of competitiveness. \par \par \uc2  "However, once our products reach the port, our competitiveness drops to number seven because of the fees," Benny told the daily Kompas. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's competitiveness further plunged to number 15 by the time its textile products reached export destinations, he said. \par \par \uc2  Benny said textile exporters have little choice but to pay these fees because failure to meet the schedule would risk a penalty from importers. \par \par \uc2  In a hearing with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  last month, API proposed some solutions, which were mostly concerned with the government's handling of the industry, to optimize performance. \par \par \uc2  API called on the government to facilitate the financial restructuring of the industry, practice clean and efficient governance and provide export support facilities. \par \par \uc2  API further called on the Ministry of Communications to abolish all excessive fees and to delay a hike in port service charges until inefficiencies and other questionable port costs were abolished. \par \par \uc2  It also appealed to the Ministry of Finance and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to optimize the function of the newly established BEI by simplifying the procurement of loans. \par \par \uc2  BEI aims to boost export, but its was criticized by some industries for its strict lending terms. \par \par \uc2  The association also urged the State Ministry of Investment and State Enterprises Development to push state port company PT Pelindo to generate revenue by improving efficiency rather than imposing excessive fees. \par \par \uc2  While directing most of its demands at the government, API called on its members to boost their exports and to continue providing jobs for the massive manpower of Indonesia. (03) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw1a0084x\par }\pa