\par\par \b \uc2  Out of hand. \b0\par\par\uc2 739 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 January 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  President Abdurrahman Wahid has effectively presented his critics with new ammunition to attack his administration. He has been accused of lacking a proper sense of crisis resulting from his offhand approach to the sectarian conflict in Maluku. Now his critics can claim that he is simply out of touch with reality, or even oblivious. His proposal to hike the salaries of all top state officials by a staggering amount starting as early as April 1 is so unbelievable that one might think it another one of his jokes. \par \par \uc2  According to leaked state documents which might be unveiled in the President's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  speech on Thursday, the take-home pay of the President would be raised more than 225 percent from Rp 32.9 million to Rp 107.4 million; that of the vice president from Rp 22 million to Rp 89.5 million; and that of Cabinet members from 5.6 million to Rp 44.75 million. To secure a smooth passage at the House, the plan offers to increase the take-home pay of legislators from Rp 5.5 million to Rp 27.65 million, and that of the House Speaker from Rp 6.38 million to Rp 45.5 million. \par \par \uc2  Even Nurcholish Madjid, a respected Muslim scholar who has previously been supportive of Abdurrahman's often erratic behavior, condemned the President's plan in no \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  terms. It is not the salary increases, but the degree of these increases that has drawn widespread criticism. Further, this kind of obscene escalation comes at a time when the nation is still reeling from a deep \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession, and when the government has barely rescued itself from near bankruptcy. \par \par \uc2  Since the plan was never officially disclosed, but rather leaked by some members of the appalled Cabinet, the government has not fully justified its proposed salary hikes to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We expect to hear the details in Thursday's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  speech, but from the limited explanations given so far, including from Minister of Finance Bambang Sudibyo, the reasoning is feeble, if not contentious. Bambang has asserted that the chairman of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA), earns much more than himself, although he oversees the chairman's activities. One could deduce then that the IBRA chairman is grossly overpaid, and not that Bambang is entitled to a raise. Another comparison with the earnings of Singapore officials, including Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, reflects the callowness of those who presented this argument. \par \par \uc2  The strongest justification for a sizable increase in the salary of state officials and civil servants is to stem rampant corruption in bureaucracy. Few people doubt that corruption is partly, though not entirely, prompted by the extremely low salaries of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector employees. Civil servants rank among the lowest paid professionals in this country. They deserve an increase, not only to stem corruption, but also to afford them a decent living and to give them fair rewards for their services and dedication. No one would argue against this, but the government's proposal is for increases in structural allowances and not for basic salaries. All signs point to a maximum increase of 20 percent in basic salary. This is a gross insult compared to the 300 to 500 percent increases their bosses are serving themselves. \par \par \uc2  Low salaries are only one factor contributing to corruption, therefore it is debatable that embezzlement will neatly disappear as a result of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector pay hikes, even if it is by a hefty amount. \par \par \uc2  The salary hike proposal has left many unanswered questions, such as how the government intends to pay for the massive increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is always a trade-off, and never a win-win solution. To spend more on salaries, the government must simply cut other \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , for example, by reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  on fuel or food. It might simply borrow the funds, probably from the International Monetary Fund. But finally, such massive increases in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector salaries and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will surely have a profound effect on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , such as another round of runaway inflation or high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  As we wait until Thursday to learn the answers to some of these questions when the President unveils the 2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan, the leaked proposal has caused irreparable damage to the reputation of the President, who has already faced mounting criticism for his failure to stop the violence in Maluku. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw1i00aoi\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  RAPBN faces two heavy challenges. \b0\par\par\uc2 558 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 January 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The draft state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (RAPBN) 2000 - set to be announced today-faces two heavy challenges, which are its abilities to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and to maintain foreign debt payment, a leading economist told Bisnis here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Arif Arryman of the Econit Advisory Group said the RAPBN this year is crucial to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, and as such its capability to stimulate growth becomes a serious challenge. \par \par \uc2  Econit, he said, is currently making a study on the efficacy of the RAPBN in terms of its ability to stimulate as well as its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability. \par \par \uc2  President Abdurrahman 'Gus Dur' Wahid is set to present the RAPBN 2000 to the House (DPR) today. \par \par \uc2  It's possible that Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri would read out the complete RAPBN. \par \par \uc2  Today will also see the signing of the letter of intent (LoI) to the IMF. \par \par \uc2  On the eve of the draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  presentation, senior economics minister Kwik Kian Gie and several \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers last night explained the RAPBN 2000 (embargoed until today) to the press. \par \par \uc2  Earlier at the House, Finance Minister Bambang Sudibyo said the RAPBN 2000 - amounting to about Rp180 trillion-assumes that growth would be 2.5%-3.5%, inflation at 4%-6%, the rupiah at 6,500-7,500 per US$, and oil price at US$16-19/barrel. \par \par \uc2  He said the RAPBN 2000 would be presented as it is, which is a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  - no longer balanced as in the past-with the assumption that the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be about 5% of the GDP, or about Rp45 trillion. \par \par \uc2  The RAPBN 2000 is also expected to mention efforts to reduce foreign loans in stages, so that in five years government foreign debt would fall significantly. \par \par \uc2  The RAPBN is said to aim at stimulating growth through higher salaries for civil servants, retired civil servants and the armed forces. \par \par \uc2  Commenting on the RAPBN, economist Muhamad Ikhsan said he sees little hopes for that. \par \par \uc2  "Do not expect to see a large multiplier effect from a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as most of the funds would be used to pay debts and interest on bank recapitalization," said Ikhsan. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, he added, it is not as yet clear how the government would spend on low-income people. \par \par \uc2  The same case with the 30% import duty on rice, a move that would benefit traders more than it would farmers or workers. \par \par \uc2  "The \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  may be caused mainly by debt repayment and bank recapitalization. This means, money is saved, not spent," he said. \par \par \uc2  Ikhsan is also worried that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  would prevent people from \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "This means that it would do little in stimulating the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." \par \par \uc2  Arif Arryman said that while the government wishes to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and to reduce foreign loans through the new state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , many things need to be addressed, especially foreign loans. \par \par \uc2  He said there are two options in reducing debts, reducing the level of money or regulating the cashflow. \par \par \uc2  The government, he added, appears to opt for controlling its debt cashflow. \par \par \uc2  But it remains to be seen what the costs would be in the future, and what other measures need to be taken, he added. \par \par \uc2  Besides scaling back new loans, the government is also trying to reschedule debt payment, a move that has come under criticism from economists as it merely eases the burden of cashflow. (ab). \par \par \uc2  (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010804dw1k00028\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI-40 rebounds. \b0\par\par\uc2 198 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 January 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA ( Bisnis): \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the bourse was evident as shares fluctuated rather erratically on a daily basis. \par \par \uc2  Information moves swiftly, forcing investors to trade with little knowledge how it would effect their investment. \par \par \uc2  As a result, some investors tend to hit and run while others prefer to wait and see. \par \par \uc2  Yesterday saw local investors dominating trading, driving the index up to 670,153. \par \par \uc2  It rose by 14.158 points or 2.16% from the day before, when the bourse panicked and fell steeply. \par \par \uc2  Local investors appear confident that the armed forces would be able to overcome the riots in Mataram and Makassar. \par \par \uc2  Investors became even more convinced when President Gus Dur said he was convinced that Indonesia would be able to come out from the crisis and emerge as a key global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  power. \par \par \uc2  When submitting the draft state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (RAPBN), which was read out by Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri, the government voiced strong optimism among investors on the future of the nation's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  This led to buying action, causing the JSX index to rise by 2.16%. However, is our current social and political situation really moving towards stability? (*). \par \par \uc2  (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010804dw1l0002f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
