\par\par \b \uc2  Editorial - GEO-POLITICS. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,010 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 January 2000\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  In one of his recent statements, Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab said that Indonesia would like to have closer relations with other Asian countries, such China and Japan, to ensure that prospects for peace remain positive in this part of the world. \par \par \uc2  Because the presence of Japan, which is the biggest foreign investor in Indonesia, is not mentioned in this set up, it may be presumed that what Shihab has in mind is some sort of an alliance which will strive to preserve peace and international understanding based on sound ethical considerations. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia is the only one of the world's larger countries which does not precess nuclear arms, and still concentrates its primary effort on obtaining the loans and foreign investment needed to get its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  going. \par \par \uc2  The United States has never approved of the fact that China and India have become nuclear powers through clandestine means. There may now well be conjecture in that country that Indonesia harbors secret plans to join the Asian nuclear club of nations. \par \par \uc2  Washington has shown itself to be such a good friend of Indonesia that it did not hesitate to order the military not to carry out a coup, instead giving President Abdurrahman Wahid a chance to restore the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and improve the living conditions of the people. \par \par \uc2  This objective, which the government has been trying to achieve, is more down to earth than the pursuit of geo-political targets. These are beyond Indonesia's power to accomplish. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  Editorial: ABDURRAHMAN'S ABSENCE \par \par \uc2  There is no doubt many Indonesians are having difficulty deciding whether to be reassured or worried that the military has put itself on heightened alert "to anticipate any possible disturbances" during President Abdurrahman Wahid's 16-day absence from the country. \par \par \uc2  The problem is that this time the President is leaving this country in a climate of grave \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The President's light-hearted refutals not withstanding, rumors of a possible military coup have refused to die. Indeed, the rumors appeared to gain in strength after Abdurrahman's departure from Jakarta on Friday. \par \par \uc2  In the already fidgety market, the rumors created enough further \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cause the Jakarta Stock Exchange to fall by around 1.5 percent on Friday. The rupiah also dropped slightly during the week. \par \par \uc2  With all this anxiety and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the country has been left in the change of Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri, whose popularity among the masses is unquestioned, but whose experience in matters of government remains untested. Given the circumstances, the best one can hope for is that Abdurrahman's confidence that nothing will happen during his 16-day absence derives from hard intelligence rather than mere intuition. \par \par \uc2  As for the Vice President, this is her opportunity to show the nation and the world that she does indeed have the capacity to lead the nation, even if it is one careful step at a time, toward a better future. - The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  - DISLOYAL SOLDIERS \par \par \uc2  In mid January, a rumor that the Indonesian Military     (TNI) would launch \par \par \uc2  a coup d'etat to topple